label: Lafayette Anticipations
comment: Lafayette Anticipations, a foundation dedicated to the arts, offers free exhibitions, workshops, tours, concerts and performances. Housed in a unique building designed by architect Rem Koolhaas / OMA, it is a place of experimentation with workshops for artists. Discover the exhibitions, relax in the Café-restaurant M?t?r and explore the Boutique!

label: Erawan
comment: In the heart of a captivating setting, between bamboo leaves and under the benevolent gaze of a dragon statuette, you can savor delicious Thai specialties. An exquisite moment for the taste buds, an unforgettable sensory experience, where exotic flavors and enchanting ambience come together to offer a culinary journey like no other. A gastronomic getaway not to be missed by all lovers of authentic, refined cuisine.

label: Au bout du champ
comment: Discover the eco-responsible market gardener revolutionizing fruit and vegetable distribution! Seasonal produce, grown locally less than 100 km from Paris by passionate growers. To limit greenhouse gas emissions, an online platform facilitates ordering. SMS sent to customers as soon as basket is prepared at "ABDC". Quality local fruit, vegetables, fresh herbs, eggs, syrups, jams and juices. A practical, fresh and ecological initiative!

label: Les Ateliers de Ménilmontant - Ménil'8
comment: Founded in 1991, the Ateliers de Ménilmontant association organizes open days in September. This is an opportunity to discover the work of local artists at exhibitions throughout the district, notably at the "Ménil'8" gallery at 8 rue Boyer. With 170 m² of light-filled space, it hosts around fifteen exhibitions a year. A great initiative to promote contemporary art and encourage exchanges between artists and the public.

label: Jardins des Champs-Élysées
comment: The gardens of the Champs-Élysées, a chic district in the 8th arrondissement of Paris, run along the capital's emblematic avenue, from Place de la Concorde to the Champs-Élysées traffic circle. Founded in 1840, they are brimming with architectural treasures, museums, entertainment venues and renowned restaurants. Nature lovers will be dazzled by the variety of trees and flower beds. A must for a stroll, this area is captivating for its beauty and history.

label: Jardin des Deux Nèthes
comment: In the heart of the 18th arrondissement, nestles the Jardin des Deux Nèthes, a 210 m² green space allocated to a local residents' association for collaborative gardening. The site offers neighborhood gardening activities and educational projects for local schools. A true haven of peace and knowledge in the heart of the city.

label: Batman Escape
comment: Discover Batman Escape for an immersive adventure inspired by the Batman universe. Explore 4 scenarios combining escape game and immersive theater in Gotham City. Meet talented actors, relax at the bar and take part in ultra-realistic remote-controlled car races. Suitable for everyone, children aged 7 and over and adults, fans or novices, ideal for Team Building. Enjoy this unique experience over 3000m² at Boom Boom Villette. Don't miss this incredible adventure!

label: Capitaine Fracasse
comment: Come aboard the Capitaine Fracasse for a 2-hour cruise on the Seine starting at 54? Depart from the Ile aux Cygnes, cross the Pont Bir-Hakeim near the Eiffel Tower to the Bibliothèque François Mitterrand. Enjoy dinner from 67? with traditional dishes: crab tartare with citrus fruits, Label Rouge farmhouse guinea fowl supreme, all-chocolate entremet. Children's menu available! A culinary experience not to be missed!

label: Camille Fournet
comment: Since 1945, Camille Fournet has been crafting watch straps of exceptional quality, perpetuating the art of master saddlers. Renowned for its expertise in exotic leathers such as alligator, ostrich, python, lizard and shagreen, it also excels in the creation of leather goods. A resolutely high-end savoir-faire at the service of elegance and authenticity.

label: Le Petit Prince de Paris
comment: Located near the Pantheon, Le Petit Prince de Paris, a gay-friendly restaurant with unique charm, is a Parisian institution. Its cuisine combines tradition and originality, with flavors from the South. Regular theme evenings with live music and entertainment. An all-male team for attentive service. A must for tasty meals and lively evenings.

label: Musée de la Contrefaçon
comment: Discover fascinating showcases featuring authentic objects alongside their counterfeits. An immersive visit that invites you to observe the details that distinguish the real from the fake. A unique opportunity to learn more about counterfeiting methods and appreciate the authenticity of original works. A captivating exhibition that prompts reflection on the value and importance of authentic craftsmanship.

label: Jardin Tino Rossi
comment: The Tino Rossi garden offers a pleasant stroll along the banks of the Seine, from the Institut du Monde Arabe to the Jardin des Plantes. The garden is home to the Musée de la Sculpture en Plein Air, where works by leading contemporary artists such as Brancusi, César, Ipoustéguy and Zadkine are on display. A must-see artistic immersion for sculpture enthusiasts.

comment: Come and discover the most fashionable eyewear from the professionals at Pont Neuf! With a style that's always ahead of the fashion curve, this boutique combines the know-how of the best contemporary designers with the recognized expertise of its opticians. A must for all fashion and optical enthusiasts!

label: Jardin de l'Intendant
comment: Designed by Robert Cotte in the 17th century, the Jardin de l'Intendant was recreated in 1980, faithful to the original plans. In perfect harmony with the chapelle des Invalides, this garden features a 19th-century statue by Ernest Dubois, in homage to Mansart. It embodies all the classic elements of French-style gardens, with its yew trees, boxwood and geometrically trimmed hedges. A celebration of symmetry and elegance, ideal for a refined, historic stroll.

label: Cathédrale Saint-Louis des Invalides - Hôtel national des Invalides
comment: The church of Saint-Louis des Invalides houses the vault of the governors, the resting place of many high-ranking military officers. Its 17th-century organ, restored in the 1950s, adorns a vault steeped in history. Today, it hosts a variety of cultural events and celebrations, including masses in memory of Napoleon I and the Hôtel des Invalides. An essential visit to discover France's rich military past.

label: Piscine Didot
comment: The Didot swimming pool, in the 14th arrondissement of Paris, is a haven for swimming enthusiasts. Its 25 m pool welcomes athletes and novices alike, with a variety of activities including swimming, aquagym and aquabike classes. In a friendly atmosphere, the Didot pool offers extended opening hours to suit all schedules. Whether you're a keen swimmer or a wellness enthusiast, this aquatic space will meet all your expectations.

label: Mombini
comment: Mombini offers parents a unique experience combining boutique and café. Come and discover original products for your children while learning baby massage techniques. Enjoy playful workshops and regular birthday parties. A friendly place for families in search of special moments.

label: Tribal Café
comment: Located near the Grands Boulevards, Tribal Café is a bar with an eye-catching oriental decor. This atypical place offers its clientele a warm and exotic atmosphere. Its reputation stems from special evenings on Fridays and Saturdays, when a delicious couscous is served, adding conviviality to the experience. With its exotic flavors and enchanting decor, Tribal Café promises unforgettable moments and total immersion in a world of escape.

label: Stade Roland-Garros
comment: Since 1927, the Roland-Garros stadium has been the absolute benchmark for clay-court tennis. Every year, this prestigious venue plays host to the French Open, the third Grand Slam of the season. For two weeks, the world's best players battle it out on the 24 courts of this legendary venue, including the famous Philippe-Chatrier and Suzanne Lenglen courts. A true ode to tennis, where the magic works on the famous ochre clay, before the eyes of tennis fans from all over the world.

label: Le Moulin de la Galette
comment: Moulin de la Galette, formerly Moulin du Palais since 1622, has been a Debray family landmark since 1809. Transformed into a guinguette in 1870, competing with the neighboring Moulin Radet, it was chosen as the only mill for the family to keep around 1895. Immortalized by Renoir in "Le Bal du Moulin de la Galette", it inspired Toulouse-Lautrec and Picasso. The last of Montmartre's thirty mills still in working order, it remains inaccessible to visitors.

comment: The Musée du Louvre bookshop-boutique, designed by RDAI Architecture, extends over 2 levels totalling almost 1,900 m². Modern and bright, this space offers a variety of worlds: art bookshop, children's area, museum art workshop (casts and prints), jewelry, accessories, decoration, art of living, stationery and reproductions of works of art. Noble materials sublimate the whole to offer a unique shopping experience.

label: Cake shop - Comptoir des pâtisseries
comment: Savor the delights of the Cake Shop at Mandarin Oriental, nestled in the luxurious Rue Saint-Honoré. Under the guidance of renowned chef Thierry Marx, this temple of pastry sublimates the great classics and seduces with its original creations. A gourmet pause not to be missed at the entrance to the Camélia restaurant, for a moment of sweetness and refinement in the heart of the capital.

label: Galignani
comment: Discover a unique bookshop offering a rich selection of Anglo-American and French books. Classics and contemporaries rub shoulders to satisfy every reading enthusiast. Immerse yourself in a warm atmosphere where literary passion is palpable on every shelf. Novels, poetry, essays, comics... You're bound to find what you're looking for in this unusual bookshop.

label: Pelouse de Reuilly
comment: The Pelouse de Reuilly, near the Bois de Vincennes, is a peaceful green space surrounded by imposing trees. Popular for public events such as concerts and craft markets, it attracts a diverse public in search of relaxation. It's the ideal green oasis to recharge your batteries in the heart of the city.

label: Bibliothèque historique de la Ville de Paris - BHVP
comment: Founded in 1871, the library moved into the 16th-century Hôtel de Lamoignon in 1969. Here you'll find books, magazines, manuscripts, maps, photos, drawings, prints, posters and postcards. These treasures trace the history of Paris and the Île-de-France region, as well as theater, literature and feminism. A goldmine for culture and heritage enthusiasts!

Each model reflects the team's craftsmanship, offering unique pieces to a sophisticated clientele in search of durability. The commitment to excellence is reflected in every detail, offering authentic products. The brand appeals to lovers of timeless design with its keen sense of style and aesthetics.

label: Lycée hôtelier Guillaume Tirel
comment: The Lycée Hôtelier Guillaume Tirel offers a true gastronomic experience with its 4 application restaurants: l'Astérie and Côté Jardin, for gourmet meals, and l'Orée and l'Aube, for brasseries. These restaurants welcome visitors for lunch and some for dinner. Lunch prices range from 18? to 22? and dinner from 22? to 27? The schedule and menus can be consulted on the website for an unforgettable culinary experience.

label: Théâtre des Bouffes du Nord
comment: The Théâtre des Bouffes du Nord, an artistic gem located in the lively La Chapelle district (18th arrondissement), embodies the quintessence of the Parisian cultural scene. Directed for many years by the eminent director Peter Brook, this legendary establishment offers a rich and eclectic program, skilfully combining music, theater, opera and dance. A veritable nugget for lovers of the performing arts in search of unique emotions and artistic discoveries.

label: Royalcheese
comment: Founded in 1998, Royalcheese has established itself as a benchmark for fashion-forward streetwear. Its selection features iconic brands such as Levi's Vintage, Wrangler, Edwin, April 77, Lyle & Scott and Sessùn. Not to be missed: the shop-in-shop dedicated to the Van's brand, a real must-have for fans of urban and trendy style.

label: Marché Maubert
comment: The Maubert market, in the heart of the Latin Quarter, is a must for gourmets. With 45 stalls offering fresh, high-quality produce, including organic fruit and vegetables, you'll be immersed in a whirlwind of flavors and colors. This market promotes healthy, ethical eating, in line with consumer expectations. Shopping here means supporting environmentally-friendly agriculture. Maubert invites you to combine pleasure and health at every meal.

label: Roller Squad Institut
comment: The only association recognized by the Roller Skating Federation promotes "citizen roller skating" and encourages initiation to the sport. Free rides, open to all (subject to 2? insurance for non-members), are regularly organized for enthusiasts throughout the year. A great opportunity to discover or perfect your skating talents in a safe and friendly atmosphere.

label: Beaugrenelle Paris
comment: Close to the Eiffel Tower and opposite the Statue of Liberty, Beaugrenelle Paris is an elegant, relaxing shopping center on the banks of the Seine. With over 100 brands ranging from fashion to homeware, a 10-screen multiplex designed by the famous designer Ora-ïto, and a variety of restaurants offering breathtaking views of the river, this place is sure to satisfy every shopping and relaxation craving.

label: Chez Françoise
comment: Come and enjoy a unique and refined culinary experience at Françoise, where the delicate and varied cuisine will delight your taste buds. Located close to the National Assembly, this establishment is a favorite with parliamentarians in search of a delicious meal. The warm, friendly atmosphere makes it the ideal place for a memorable lunch. Don't hesitate any longer and come and discover this not-to-be-missed address for an unforgettable moment of gustatory pleasure.

label: Le Derrière
comment: In the heart of the capital, Le Derrière is an atypical restaurant, discreet from the outside. Inside, a surprise awaits you: a cosy apartment with living room, bathroom and kitchen. The home cooking revisits French classics with flair. Between courses, ping-pong, reading and cinema are on offer. Don't miss the secret of the cupboard! Le Derrière is a culinary experience not to be missed.

label: Marché aux fleurs
comment: On the Île de la Cité is the flower market on Place Louis Lépine, between Notre-Dame and the Sainte-Chapelle, opened in 1830. This market offers a wide selection of flowers and plants under 1900s-era pavilions, from local species to exotic varieties such as orchids. In Paris, don't miss the Madeleine and Ternes markets for daily floral diversity. Explore the capital's plant treasures!

label: Musée de l'Orangerie
comment: At the Musée de l'Orangerie, two rooms highlight Claude Monet's Water Lilies, a gift to France in 1922. These impressive canvases captivate with their beauty and artistic richness. Descending to the basement, visitors discover the Jean Walter and Paul Guillaume collection, a selection of works by 20th-century masters such as Renoir, Cézanne, Matisse, Picasso and Soutine. A fascinating immersion into the artistic universe of these great names in art history.

label: Cultural Paris
comment: Certified as a Guide-conférencière Nationale by the French Ministries of Tourism and Culture, I invite you to discover Paris through exciting tours in Russian. Museums, monuments, picturesque districts and unusual places, as well as trips to Versailles, Fontainebleau or Chantilly, will hold no secrets for you. Whether you're on your own or in a group, I'm committed to sharing my love of this unique city with you.

label: Le Dépôt Légal - Christophe Adam
comment: Renowned pastry chef Christophe Adam brilliantly directs the Dépôt Légal, an exceptional venue located between the Palais Royal and the Bourse. From breakfast to after-work, lunch and tea time, every moment of the day is enhanced by a varied menu. Sundays are reserved for a delicious brunch. The warm, contemporary setting was designed by talented architects Francesca Errico and Olivier Delannoy of the Reinh agency.

label: Paroisse Saint-Roch
comment: Built between 1653 and 1754, this church perched on a hillock is home to the tombs of such luminaries as Corneille, Le Nôtre and Diderot. Designed in successive chapels, its nave and choir are the work of architect Jacques Lemercier, famous for the Sorbonne. John Law, an influential parishioner, contributed to the vaulting during the Regency period. Despite the disappearance of its sculpted façade, Father Marduel commissioned Jean-Baptiste Pierre to decorate the dome with a "Triumph of the Virgin".

label: Virage
comment: Virage, located between the 17th arrondissement and Saint-Ouen, is an open-air venue that livens up Parisian nights. Its eclectic program features LGBTQIA+ communities. Open, inclusive, multi-disciplinary and responsible, it is located on the site of a former pound where carcasses have been skilfully reused to create an original décor, accompanied by lush nature reclaiming its rights. A unique setting for unforgettable night-time experiences.

comment: Take advantage of our IT self-service services including PC/Mac, scanners, A4/A3 color or black & white printers, A4/A3 color copier, engraving and DTP services. Quality equipment to meet all your printing and document processing needs.

label: Chez Mamane
comment: Couscous is a delicious dish featuring perfect semolina, tasty vegetables, chicken, leg of lamb, merguez sausages... Both tasty and affordable, this convivial meal is a real treat for the taste buds. Good humor reigns at the table, prices are low, and every bite transports us straight to the heart of Oriental cuisine. A culinary experience not to be missed!

label: Jardin des Arènes de Montmartre
comment: The Jardin des Arènes de Montmartre, near the Sacré-C?ur Basilica, offers a magnificent view of Paris. This haven of greenery, usually inaccessible, is open for special events. Visitors can stroll among the Roman ruins and relax in the tranquil setting. Close to the basilica, it's an ideal walk for tourists. Discover this hidden gem on your next visit to Paris!

comment: Le Nouvel Odéon cinema offers a variety of films to suit all tastes: from animated classics to musicals and family favorites. Don't miss the Sunday Kid Odéon children's program, in partnership with "L'Enfance de l'Art". It's a great opportunity to enjoy quality cinema with the whole family.

label: Paradis Latin
comment: In the heart of the Latin Quarter, the Paradis Latin, restored by Gustave Eiffel in 1889 and created by Napoleon in 1803, has been presenting its new revue "L?Oiseau Paradis", directed by Kamel Ouali, since May 2019. Dièse, a finalist on "The Voice" in 2013, shines as a new star. With a spellbinding pre-show and dinner by three-Michelin-star Guy Savoy, this is a unique experience. A show combining artistic talent and advanced technology for a dynamic, poetic and sensual evening.

label: Paroisse Saint-Joseph Artisan
comment: In the 10th arrondissement, the Saint-Joseph l'Artisan church, close to the Parc des Buttes-Chaumont and the Bassin de la Villette, illustrates the neo-Gothic style of the 19th century. Although small in size, it is distinguished by its sober decor. The interior is bathed in natural light, thanks to stained glass windows mostly decorated with light geometric motifs, with the exception of three more colorful ones. A visit that promises a peaceful, luminous atmosphere.

label: Le Bon Marché Rive Gauche
comment: Le Bon Marché Rive Gauche, founded in 1852 in the Saint-Germain-des-Prés district, is the first department store in Paris. A true emblem of French refinement, it offers a cutting-edge selection of fashion, furniture and delicatessen. Every year at Christmas, its magnificently decorated windows transport passers-by into a magical world. A must for lovers of luxury and French tradition.

label: Maison de la Poésie - Scène littéraire
comment: The Maison Artistique is transformed into a warm, inviting space for literary exchange, inspiring encounters and lively debate. Open to readings and creations, it gives voice to poets and writers. Benevolent, innovative and welcoming, it sets itself apart from theaters to devote itself fully to authors, literature and its modernity.

label: Le Petit Bouillon Pharamond
comment: In the heart of Les Halles is the famous historic restaurant founded by Alexandre Pharamond in the 19th century. Specializing in French cuisine, particularly from Normandy, it offers quality dishes at affordable prices. Connoisseurs can savor the delicious tripe à la mode de Caen, the house specialty. The exceptional, listed early 20th-century setting combines wood panelling, painted mirrors and pâte de verre. Recommended by Gault & Millau.

comment: Located at the foot of the Beaugrenelle shopping center, the René et André Mourlon sports center offers top-quality facilities. It features a multi-purpose basketball court, which can be converted into a handball court, and mini-tennis courts for younger children. A 200-metre athletics track is also available for running enthusiasts. It's the perfect place to practice a variety of sports in a modern, dynamic environment.

Whether for general, school or university reading, this establishment offers a wide and varied selection of books. A must for all book lovers in search of good deals and unique literary finds.

label: Beaupassage
comment: Located in the heart of the 7th arrondissement between Rue de Grenelle, Rue du Bac and Boulevard Raspail, Beaupassage is a gastronomic haven of peace. Great French chefs such as Yannick Alléno, Pierre Hermé and Anne-Sophie Pic propose their delights here. Contemporary works of art by Fabrice Hyber and Stefan Rinck adorn the space, with charming terraces to enjoy the peaceful ambience. An unmissable culinary getaway from the hustle and bustle of Parisian life.

label: Ground Zero
comment: Come and discover a record shop dedicated to independent music, offering a vast selection of new vinyl, quality reissues and rare second-hand items. Immerse yourself in a unique musical universe, where each vinyl tells a story and promises an incomparable sensory experience. A must for lovers of authentic sound and underground music.

label: Bar Le 47
comment: Le 47, located in the Château Frontenac hotel, offers an elegant blend of modernity and art deco. This spacious bar is prized for its tea time during the day and its refined cocktail menu in the evening, prepared with care by an expert barman. A must-visit address in Paris's Golden Triangle, with a warm, cosy atmosphere. Enter this exceptional place through a superb wrought-iron door and let yourself be charmed by its unique atmosphere.

The Galerie du 19M offers a convivial space, transcending borders, for all ages.

label: L'Occitane - Paris Arcole
comment: The L'Occitane brand, drawing on its Provencal origins, uses the benefits of phytotherapy and aromatherapy to design its skincare products and fragrances. Committed to animal welfare, the company favors the use of natural products while guaranteeing that they are not tested on animals. This ethical approach contributes to the brand's renown, combining authenticity, well-being and respect for the environment.

The French Trotters clothing line, launched in 2010, is also showcased in this space.

label: Paris Gay Village
comment: ParisGayVillage, an association under the French law of 1901, brings together enthusiasts wishing to promote LGBT tourism in Paris. Passionate members guide you through the city's gay and lesbian scene, combining culture and conviviality. Discover the history of homosexual cultures through unique guided tours organized every month. An original and enriching way to explore the diversity of Paris.

label: Francis Kurkdjian
comment: Francis Kurkdjian, renowned for his iconic creations such as Jean Paul Gaultier's Le Mâle, made perfume history by becoming the first to open a bespoke perfume atelier. A pioneer, he also founded his own Maison de Parfums, continuing his olfactory heritage with excellence and audacity.

label: Fondation Jérôme Seydoux-Pathé
comment: The Fondation Jérôme Seydoux-Pathé, created in 2006, protects Pathé's rich heritage of over 10,000 films and diverse collections. The building, designed by Renzo Piano, includes a research center, rooms for collections and exhibitions. Educational activities are also organized for the public.

label: 86Champs - L'Occitane et Pierre Hermé
comment: 86Champs, on a beautiful avenue in Paris, combines the renowned brands L'Occitane and Pierre Hermé for a unique experience. The counter offers macaroons, chocolates and pastries, as well as L'Occitane beauty products. To prolong the pleasure, a stop at the barista or restaurant is recommended. 86Champs, an exceptional address combining art de vivre and gastronomy, not to be missed.

comment: Discover the Voyage restaurant, open until 2am for a unique culinary experience. With a Héritage 1905 menu and mini-dishes concocted by chefs in residence. Don't miss the KRUG STUDIO for tailor-made musical and gastronomic pairings. Add restaurant Ernest, a contemporary brasserie run by Michelin-starred chef Naoëlle d?Hainaut. A refined venue signed by designer Constance Guisset for a successful gourmet getaway.

comment: This French perfumery chain offers an impressive variety of products and services, from fragrances and cosmetics to body care and accessories. In addition, it offers beauty institutes and advice bars. With over 80 outlets in Paris, it is an essential reference for all beauty lovers seeking quality and diversity.

label: Studio Galande
comment: Nestled in the heart of the Latin Quarter, the Studio Galande is a magnet for lovers of arthouse cinema. Its cozy 83-seat auditorium offers a varied selection of classic and contemporary films. Don't miss: on Fridays and Saturdays, the Studio Galande is sold out for the cult screening of Rocky Horror Picture Show, a true 70s gem. An unforgettable cinematic experience in a friendly atmosphere.

label: Église Saint-Eustache
comment: In the heart of Les Halles, Saint-Eustache church is a prized Paris icon. Its imposing dimensions and art-rich interior make it unique. Built in 1532, it blends Gothic, Renaissance and Classical styles. Its great organ, the largest in France, attracts music lovers to concerts conducted by a renowned organist. Saint-Eustache hosts prestigious ensembles and renowned festivals all year round, to the delight of music lovers.

label: L'Avant-Goût
comment: The restaurant L'Avant-Goût, nestled in the Butte-aux-Cailles district, stands out as a "contemporary bistro" appreciated by fine palates and lovers of good food in Paris. Its cuisine delights the taste buds of locals and visitors alike, combining tradition and creativity to offer a unique and refined gastronomic experience. A must for food lovers.

label: Maison de Victor Hugo
comment: Discover the world of Victor Hugo at his home on Place de Vosges, in the Marais district. From his private home to the Hôtel particulier where he created "Les Misérables", explore his life through objects and settings. The second floor showcases his drawings and writings. Enjoy tours and workshops for children, or visit the library by appointment. A true immersion in this unique literary universe.

label: Yoyo
comment: Le Yoyo, located on the premises of the Cinémathèque Française in the Palais de Tokyo, is a versatile venue for concerts, DJ sets, contemporary art exhibitions, private parties and fashion shows. Its varied program attracts a hip audience, especially clubbers who are fans of electronic music at weekends. Two screening rooms, Madame Cinéma and Mademoiselle Cinéma, add a cinematic touch to the Yoyo experience.

label: Galerie Colbert
comment: The Galerie Colbert, built in 1823 near the Galerie Vivienne, is an elegant covered gallery belonging to the Bibliothèque Nationale. It houses the Institut National d'Histoire de l'Art (INHA) and the Institut National du Patrimoine (INP), and boasts a magnificent rotunda with a glass dome. The "Le Grand Colbert" brasserie, a listed historic monument, is located at the entrance and is popular with cinema-goers for its Art Nouveau style.

comment: A symbol of French elegance, Ladurée shines at 75 avenue des Champs-Élysées. Spread over 1,000 m² on 2 levels, it's a true immersion in French art de vivre. Restaurant, winter garden, music room, café, dessert bar, pastry school and Ladurée macaroon boutique enchant gourmets. An unmissable address for savoring French gastronomy.

comment: Our classes promote relaxation and oxygenation through breathing. Yoga, Pilates, Qi Gong and barre strengthen muscles and flexibility. Sophrology promotes personal development. comment: Discover this luxury Brasserie classified as a Historic Monument, immersed in Parisian history with its authentic 1900s Art Nouveau setting. Renowned among Parisian brasseries, this address opposite the Saint-Lazare train station is a century-old treasure. A unique gastronomic experience just 2 minutes from the Grands Magasins, Place de la Concorde and Opéra Garnier.

label: Parc Clichy-Batignolles - Martin Luther King
comment: The park is full of surprises with its atypical layout: the rail garden features deckchairs, a children's play area and sports fields. And let's not forget the landscaped pond, a veritable oasis housing a diversity of aquatic and waterside plants: water lilies, irises, reeds, flowering rushes... A truly rich and varied ecosystem to discover.

label: Galanga
comment: Located in the heart of the Hôtel Monsieur George in the 8th arrondissement of Paris, the Galanga restaurant offers cuisine inspired by the flavors of the world by chef Thomas Danigo. A former chef at the Hôtel La Ponche in Saint Tropez, he puts the spotlight on vegetables in a warm setting designed by Anouska Hempel. Galanga Paris dishes, enhanced by exotic spices and condiments, offer a unique gastronomic experience.

label: Stade Pierre de Coubertin
comment: Located near the Parc des Princes, the Stade Coubertin, opened in 1937, hosts major sporting events. Every year, it hosts prestigious competitions such as the Fencing World Cup, the GDF Suez Tennis Open and the French International Badminton Championships. Its history has also been punctuated by highlights such as the Badminton World Championships in 2010 and the finals of the French Men's Volleyball Championship in 2011 and 2012. An emblematic venue for passion, competition and sporting performance.

label: Le Tambour
comment: Located in the lively Etienne Marcel district, Le Tambour is a popular bar for Parisian night owls. Its charming little terrace and quirky decor, combining road signs and old posters, give it a unique atmosphere. Its simple but tasty cuisine is a godsend for hungry stomachs at 3am. Le Tambour is the perfect address for a late-night snack in a friendly, relaxed atmosphere.

comment: Bibimbap, an authentic Korean restaurant near the Museum of Natural History, offers delicious, healthy cuisine. The dishes are tasty, without excess sauce or fat, promoting well-being. The must-try Bibimbap and Ssambap, accompanied by soup, are the stars of the menu. Service is distinguished by its attentiveness to customers. An address to discover for a balanced culinary experience with a change of scenery.

A true festival for the taste buds, where flavors and aromas mingle to delight lovers of fine produce. A must for gourmets in search of quality and authenticity.

label: Square Alexandre et René Parodi
comment: The Square Alexandre et René Parodi, in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, is the largest in the region. With a variety of games for all ages and magnificent artistic statues, it's ideal for a family stroll, a break with friends or to enjoy nature in the city. This haven of peace in the heart of Paris is perfect for those seeking tranquillity and greenery in the city.

label: Le Nélie
comment: The Jacquemart-André museum, near the Champs-Élysées in Paris, exhibits a varied art collection in a 19th-century mansion. The Café Jacquemart-André, set in a sumptuous dining room, offers an exceptional culinary experience. Louis XV consoles, 18th-century tapestries, Tiepolo frescoes, gilding and crystal chandeliers create a warm atmosphere. Le Café welcomes gourmets for a sweet break or a refined lunch, outside the museum.

comment: Café Chéri(e), Belleville's flagship bar, seduces with its friendly atmosphere and red neon decor. A pioneer in Wi-Fi, it attracts a varied clientele. Its contested terrace is a privilege. Happy hour (5pm-8pm) is a must, as are weekend DJ sets. On the 1st floor, captivating art exhibitions await lovers of lively, cosmopolitan moments. An unmissable address for night owls in search of discovery.

label: Gare Saint-Lazare
comment: Located in the 8th arrondissement, Gare Saint-Lazare has been a key Paris landmark since 1837. With 120 million visitors a year, it offers connections to the western Paris region and Normandy. Close to department stores, it's perfect for shopping and dining. Three floors house boutiques, restaurants, a gym and various services. The Passerelle de l'Impératrice Eugénie and the Musée d'Art Ludique enrich this dynamic cultural hub.

Her creations are distinguished by their clean lines, brightly colored leather lining and saddle stitching in ecru thread. Each piece, whether small series or one-offs, embodies the designer's elegance and craftsmanship.

comment: Nestled in the heart of the lively Montorgueil district, Jefrey's is a real gem for cocktail lovers. In a jazzy, retro atmosphere, this bar offers a wide choice of creative and revisited cocktails. The comfortable purple sofas invite you to relax, while customers watch in fascination as the talented waiters expertly prepare the drinks. A true sensory experience not to be missed for those in search of a unique and memorable moment.

label: Opéra national de Paris - Palais Garnier
comment: Inaugurated in 1875, the Palais Garnier is an architectural gem designed by Charles Garnier. The thirteenth opera house in Paris since it was founded by Louis XIV, its construction was decided by Napoleon III as part of Haussmann's works. A historic monument open to visitors, it offers lyrical and choreographic performances. Don't miss the ceiling painted by Chagall.

label: Mori Venice Bar
comment: Massimo Mori, renowned Italian chef in Paris, delights gourmets with his Venetian specialties. In a chic setting designed by Philippe Starck, guests are transported into an elegant universe. An exceptional culinary experience awaits them, where subtle flavors and quality products blend perfectly. Massimo Mori's restaurant is a jewel of Italian gastronomy in Paris, offering an unforgettable gourmet escapade.

label: Bizz'Art
comment: Come and discover an unmissable venue for music lovers! This bar-restaurant is the place to be for fans of gospel, jazz, soul, funk, world music and Latin-Brazilian music. With its stage, it offers a friendly, lively atmosphere where music lovers can enjoy fiery concerts in a warm ambience. It's the ideal place to savor the enchanting sounds and spend an unforgettable moment in the company of talented musicians.

label: Église Notre-Dame de la Gare
comment: In the heart of the district between the Place d'Italie and the Bibliothèque Nationale de France, stands Notre-Dame de la Gare, a sacred building since 1859. Its choir, renovated in the 50s by Anders Osterlind and Jean-François Dolbeau, will captivate lovers of sacred art. Not to be forgotten is the majestic organ dating from 1863, the work of the famous organ builder Aristide Cavaillé-Coll, adding a musical touch to this place steeped in history.

label: Musée national Picasso-Paris
comment: The Musée National Picasso-Paris is housed in the 17th-century Hôtel Salé, in the heart of the Marais district. It holds the largest public collection of works by Picasso, with over 5,000 works and 200,000 archive items. This artistic treasure trove comes from donations by the painter's heirs and his own archives, showcasing every facet of his art. In addition to temporary exhibitions, the museum offers a wide range of cultural events.

label: Les Deux Magots
comment: Founded in 1884, Les Deux Magots embodies the soul of Saint-Germain-des-Prés. Its Art Deco room and terraces offer a unique view of the church. A popular spot for observing Parisian life, it offers refined French cuisine. Its varied menu, designed around seasonal produce, combines coffee, pastries and cocktails. As a restaurant and cultural space, it hosts jazz concerts and literary gatherings.

A popular spot for observing Parisian life, it offers refined French cuisine. Its varied menu, designed around seasonal produce, combines coffee, pastries and cocktails. As a restaurant and cultural space, it hosts jazz concerts and literary gatherings.

comment: Welcome to l'Avenue, the ideal place to enjoy fine drinks and relax. Immerse yourself in an enchanting atmosphere and let yourself be charmed by our delicate flavors and attentive service. Our dedicated team looks after your well-being to make your visit an unforgettable experience. Come and enjoy a unique experience at l'Avenue, where every moment is conducive to relaxation and pleasure.

At the heart of this brand, excellence is revealed through creations of incomparable quality.

comment: Since 1931, Ateliers du Palais has been creating bespoke jewelry with exceptional craftsmanship, respecting the traditions of French jewelry-making. Their talented craftsmen create one-of-a-kind pieces, and also offer stone setting and jewelry transformation services. Each creation is stamped "Joaillerie de France" to ensure its quality. Express your ideas and offer a personalized piece of jewelry to your loved one at Ateliers du Palais.

label: Hôtel national des Invalides
comment: Built in 1670 by Louis XIV for invalid soldiers, the Hôtel Royal des Invalides is an iconic Paris landmark. It houses the Ministry of Defense and the Army Museum. The Dôme and Saint-Louis des Invalides churches add to its rich heritage. Following restoration work launched in 1981, this site steeped in history now offers visitors a memorable spectacle.

label: Cali Sisters
comment: Discover the delights of the American West Coast at Cali Sisters, located near the Palais Brongniart in Paris. This restaurant transports you straight to California with its tasty cuisine, from breakfast to dinner. Let yourself be seduced by a sunny, exotic atmosphere in the heart of the capital. A culinary voyage of Californian vibes not to be missed.

label: Eleven Paris
comment: Eleven Paris T-shirts feature quirky illustrations of personalities such as Sid Vicious, Alf and even Barack Obama, in a timeless punk-rock spirit that appeals to a wide audience. With the slogan "Life is a joke", the brand sets itself apart by offering original, trendy collections for men and women in search of style and originality. Eleven Paris clothes pay homage to pop and underground culture, while remaining affordable for all.

label: Divellec
comment: Located close to the Invalides in the 7th arrondissement, the Divellec restaurant is one of the must-visit restaurants in Paris. Headed by talented Michelin-starred chef Mathieu Pacaud, this establishment is renowned for its refined, flavorful marine cuisine. A renowned address for seafood lovers.

label: Le Chardenoux - Cyril Lignac
comment: Listed as a Monument Historique in 1908, Le Chardenoux was created by the Chardenoux family from Lozère. Renovated by chef Cyril Lignac in 2009, the "arts deco" ambience is unique, with walls adorned with mirrors and a bar inlaid with 14 marbles. At Le Chardenoux, Cyril Lignac revisits French cuisine, combining tradition and creativity to highlight local produce.

label: Paroisse Saint-Nicolas des Champs
comment: The church of Saint-Nicolas-des-Champs in Paris is a masterpiece of flamboyant Gothic architecture steeped in history. Stained glass windows, sculptures and paintings bear witness to its glorious past. Each stone tells a story, immersing visitors in the Gothic era. The Sainte Rita chapel is an ideal place for meditation. To visit Saint-Nicolas-des-Champs is to travel through the history of art and faith, offering a unique experience.

label: Ateliers d'Artistes - Les Frigos
comment: Les Frigos, a refrigerated building dating from 1921, became a unique venue in 1980 for 120 arts and crafts professionals. With 87 studios, painters, sculptors, photographers, architects, dressmakers, stylists and luthiers rub shoulders. Threatened in 1992 by the construction of Paris Rive Gauche, this emblematic site has been preserved by its occupants. The open house at the end of May is the perfect opportunity to discover this breeding ground of talent.

label: Maje
comment: Judith Milgrom has made her mark with creative, accessible collections inspired by ethno-chic. For this designer, a garment is more than just an outfit, it's a story to be told. In addition to a refined women's line, she also offers a range specially designed for little girls.

label: Fleux
comment: Fleux embodies the perfect fusion of modernity and refinement, creativity and chic. Decorative treasures carefully selected from the most renowned brands include Hervé Matejewski, Ron Arad, Fornasetti and even Vivienne Westwood. A veritable Ali Baba's cave for lovers of design and originality, located in the heart of the capital.

Enjoy an exceptional culinary experience in an elegant and friendly setting, where refinement and conviviality are perfectly harmonized.

label: La Bellevilloise
comment: La Bellevilloise, founded in 1877, is a multi-disciplinary cultural venue in Paris covering 4 levels and over 2,000m². Cafés, concerts, exhibitions, debates and markets are all on offer. An artistic space open to all, with a variety of events: concerts, exhibitions, fashion shows, ciné-mix. Discover this dynamic, community-oriented architectural heritage.

The latter brilliantly dressed the England team at the London Olympics. A veritable temple of fashion and sport, where fans of the brand with the three stripes can discover the latest novelties and the most prestigious collaborations.

Its varied international program is both demanding and accessible, offering visual and multidisciplinary entertainment. A place for exchange between audiences and artists, it celebrates cultural diversity. Its bar, green terrace and original 70s circus-style dressing rooms invite discovery and wonder.

With his unique creations of tablets, macaroons, croquants, pastries and other delicacies, he embodies luxury and savoir-faire à la française. A must for chocolate lovers in search of excellence and elegance.

Close to the city's most popular clubs and venues, Sans-Souci is a must for Pigalle's lively nights. A festive, friendly atmosphere not to be missed!

label: Fontaines Landowski
comment: The monumental fountains "Les Sources de la Seine" in the Place de la Porte de Saint-Cloud are an Art Deco work by Paul Landowski for the 1937 Universal Exhibition. Their ten-meter-high design symbolizes the artistic evolution of Paris, attracting attention for their creative ingenuity. They enrich urban aesthetics and showcase public art and sculpture in Paris.

His stores, on rue des Lombards and rue Mouffetard, offer some thirty flavors ranging from the classic to the fanciful. Alberto's Gelati", with their original shapes and generous fillings, appeal to Parisians in search of unique, delicious flavors. A must for ice cream lovers in search of new sensations.

label: Bulgari
comment: The renown of Bulgari's haute joaillerie creations, such as the famous Serpenti collection, has transcended the ages, being worn by icons such as Sophia Loren, Elizabeth Taylor and Rachel Weisz. The Italian house stands out for its excellence and relentless pursuit of quality, from jewelry to watches, perfumes, accessories and cosmetics. Bulgari embodies unrivalled expertise and a touch of timeless elegance.

label: Bibliothèque Forney
comment: In the heart of the Hôtel de Sens, one of the few remaining examples of medieval civil architecture in Paris, nestles the Forney library. With its 23,000 books, over 50,000 exhibition catalogs, 4,000 periodical titles and precious iconographic collections, it is a veritable treasure trove for lovers of the decorative arts, crafts, fine arts, graphic arts, fashion, advertising and design. A mine of information and inspiration to be discovered without delay!

comment: Since 1880, Brasserie Lipp has been an emblematic institution in Saint-Germain-des-Prés, frequented by Gide, Malraux, Proust and Camus. Nicknamed the "branch of the Chambre des Députés", it offers top-quality Alsatian and Auvergne cuisine. A mythical place where the literary past can be savored as much as its succulent dishes.

And for an elegant touch, opt for linens in the Tour d?Argent colors.

comment: For over a century, J. M. Weston shoes have been handcrafted, respecting the brand's traditional values. Under the artistic direction of Michel Perry, these emblematic models are reinvented while preserving the brand's ancestral know-how. A heritage of quality and excellence that has endured for generations.

label: Homer Lobster
comment: Come and discover a little corner of New England hidden behind the Centre Pompidou, between Le Marais and Châtelet, where you can enjoy delicious lobster sandwiches, also known as lobster rolls on the other side of the Atlantic. A second address is also available near Odéon. Don't miss the opportunity to taste this North American specialty in a charming and exotic setting in the heart of Paris.

label: Le Grand Café Capucines
comment: Inaugurated in 1875, the Grand Café Capucines is now an iconic Paris landmark, popular with locals and tourists alike. Rehabilitated by architects Hugo Toro and Maxime Liautard, the restaurant has rediscovered its charm of yesteryear with elegance and modernity, blending history and contemporaneity. Its bright new façade and revamped interiors offer a timeless atmosphere. Open 24/7, the menu reflects the very essence of brasserie.

label: L'Oiseau blanc
comment: The L'Oiseau Blanc restaurant, located on the 6th floor of the luxury Peninsula hotel, offers breathtaking views of the Eiffel Tower and Parisian rooftops. Its summer terrace makes it one of the capital's most popular rooftops. Its bistronomic menu, prepared according to the market and the seasons, will seduce the taste buds of fine gourmets.

label: Paroisse Saint-Augustin
comment: Built between 1860 and 1871, the Victor Baltard church, a blend of Romanesque and Byzantine art, stands at the junction of the boulevards Haussmann and Malesherbes. Its imposing dome rises 80 meters above a building almost 100 meters high, made of metal and cast iron with decorative angels. Inside, increasingly elaborate chapels line the path of the faithful as they approach the choir.

Immerse yourself in French culture and history for emotional moments.

comment: Although born in Canada, Tara Jarmon's creations exude Parisian elegance. Located near the Canal Saint-Martin, her brand embodies a chic, timeless, sober and resolutely feminine style. The designer's clothes appeal to an international clientele in search of refinement and audacity.

label: Prescription Cocktail Club
comment: At the Prescription Cocktail Club in Saint-Germain-des-Prés, mixology is sublimated in a cosy, select atmosphere. Discover the "Gorille dans l?agrume", a must-have cocktail, and enjoy finger food and gourmet small plates. Melon hat lamps and a library of antique books add a touch of originality. On weekdays, let yourself be enchanted by the sounds of jazz, and at weekends, enjoy the rhythm of frenzied Dj sets. A unique and refined experience not to be missed!

Listed as a historic monument, this theater is distinguished by its programming centered on great comedies, offering spectators unforgettable moments of laughter and entertainment.

label: Paris Boat Club - Escale Louvre
comment: Discover Paris on a yacht with a skipper thanks to Paris Boat Club! Private cruises for up to 8 people, with fridge and toilet on board. Hour-and-a-half, two-hour or longer cruises, with meals. Embark from Escale du Louvre or Beaugrenelle, passing Notre Dame and the Eiffel Tower. Champagne or wine tasting while admiring the monuments from the Seine. Annual subscription for an even richer experience. An unforgettable Parisian experience!

It's the perfect place to enjoy a richly emotional evening of music in the heart of Paris.

label: Unico
comment: Lovers of good meat and quality wines, let yourself be seduced by this Argentinian butcher's shop with its retro 70s style. Among the must-tries: the famous lomo with chimichurri sauce. A must for asado fans. You'll also find the same friendly atmosphere at 10 rue Amélie, 75007 Paris.

label: Paradox Museum Paris
comment: Immerse yourself in the fascinating world of the Paradox Museum, a 1700m² space dedicated to the wonders of the physical sciences and optical illusions, located near the Opéra. Ideal for an outing with family or friends, accessible to all, with café and store for a complete experience. Book on paradoxmuseumparis.com. Open daily, 10am-10pm.

label: Le Louxor - Palais du cinéma
comment: Le Louxor, built in 1921, is a neo-Egyptian-style cinema. Closed in 1988, it avoided demolition and reopened on April 17, 2013. It's a unique venue in Paris's 18th arrondissement, offering recent films as well as classics. Children can also enjoy the "Les p'tits loux" cycle and school screenings. Le Louxor is a cultural oasis in the heart of La Chapelle, a must-see for Parisian cinephiles.
description: Le Louxor, built in 1921, is a neo-Egyptian-style cinema. Closed in 1988, it avoided demolition and reopened on April 17, 2013. It's a unique venue in Paris's 18th arrondissement, offering recent films as well as classics. Children can also enjoy the "Les p'tits loux" cycle and school screenings. Le Louxor is a cultural oasis in the heart of La Chapelle, a must-see for Parisian cinephiles.

A tradition of excellence combining craftsmanship and contemporary flair.

label: Bibliothèque Nationale de France - Richelieu
comment: The Richelieu site of the Bibliothèque nationale de France is a cultural landmark in Paris, with its garden, terrace, Rose Bakery café, bookshop and Salle Ovale. Discover unique treasures such as the Berthouville Treasure, the Salle de Luynes and the Salon Louis XV. Don't miss the Galerie Mazarin, featuring treasures from the Sainte-Chapelle and Saint-Denis Basilicas. Immerse yourself in this cultural haven in the Louvre-Opéra district.

In winter, the restaurant is transformed into an elegant chalet where guests can warm up by the fireplace while savoring traditional French cuisine. An unmissable address for a gourmet break in the heart of nature.

A Parisian getaway with authentic cuisine and an exceptional view for unforgettable moments.

label: La Géode
comment: La Géode, in the heart of La Villette, is a unique cinema with a spherical structure 36 m in diameter. Its 1,000 m² screen and capacity for 400 spectators offer an exceptional visual experience thanks to Omnimax technology, projecting images nine times larger than 35 mm. Designed by architect Adrien Fainsilber, it has been enlarging moviegoers' field of vision since its inauguration in May 1985.

label: Aux Merveilleux de Fred
comment: In the Marais district, a store famous for its Merveilleux delights sweet tooths. This emblematic Northern French pastry combines meringue and whipped cream. Frédéric Vaucamps offers 5 delicious variations: Magnifique, Sans-Culotte, Excentrique, Impensable and Incroyable. Discover these tasty creations, as well as revisits of traditional cramiques, delicious brioche rolls. A gourmet escapade to savour without moderation!

label: Cinéma du Panthéon
comment: Nestled near the Pantheon in the heart of the Latin Quarter, the Cinéma du Panthéon is a Parisian gem dating from 1907. A testament to the history of cinema in the capital, it offers film cycles, ciné-clubs, debates and artistic encounters. After the screening, the Salon, decorated by Catherine Deneuve and Christian Sapet, is ideal for a gourmet break, with its warm terrace. A must for film buffs. (395 characters)

label: Marché Bourse
comment: The Place de la Bourse food market, opposite the Palais Brongniart, opens in the afternoon, ideal for local residents and employees of nearby offices. You'll discover a wide selection of fresh produce: fruit, vegetables, cheeses, bakery and delicatessen. The lively atmosphere invites you to meet new local producers and enjoy fresh dishes. A Parisian institution offering a unique shopping experience for local residents and workers.

label: Odéon - Théâtre de l'Europe/Les Ateliers Berthier
comment: Built in 1895 by architect Charles Garnier for the Opéra de Paris, the Ateliers Berthier were used as a temporary venue by the Odéon between 2002 and 2006, during the renovation of its historic auditorium. In May 2005, the Ateliers Berthier officially became the second theatre of the Odéon-Théâtre de l'Europe, with a capacity of 390 spectators.

Heir to a historic factory, it combines the aura of bricks of yesteryear with a modern design by Frédéric Borel, offering a wealth of cultural activities.

label: Laiterie de la Chapelle
comment: Laiterie de la Chapelle, 35 km from Paris, produces artisan cheeses using raw milk from cows in the French Vexin Regional Nature Park. Transparency is reflected in the workshop and cellar, visible from the street. The boutique offers tomme La Chapelle, Dormoy, Pajol, yoghurts and creamery products. A delicatessen showcases local artisanal products. Tomme-making workshops available for enthusiasts.

label: Le Faham
comment: The Faham restaurant in Batignolles, one Michelin star and two Gault & Millau toques in 2020. Its name comes from an orchid from Reunion Island, used in rhum arrangés. Chef Kelly, from "Top Chef", and her husband Jérôme, a pastry chef, offer refined, colorful cuisine with the sunny flavors of Réunion Island. An unmissable address for an authentic culinary experience.

label: Kong
comment: At the top of the Samaritaine is Kong, an extraordinary restaurant designed by Philippe Starck. Blending Japanese and 17th-century French influences, the daring glass and Plexiglas décor is a real eye-catcher. Chef Richard Pommies offers a Franco-Japanese fusion cuisine, a subtle blend of the two cultures. With music by Béatrice Ardisson and a panoramic terrace, Kong offers a unique sensory experience.

Enjoy a unique gastronomic experience from Monday to Thursday for lunch, and Tuesdays and Thursdays for dinner. Taste excellence in the making from 15?, offering a glimpse of the future of haute cuisine.

label: Brasserie Barbès
comment: Brasserie Barbès, in the multicultural Goutte d'Or district, is a superb early 20th-century building opposite Le Louxor cinema. With its 750 sq. m. of light, it offers a café-restaurant on the first floor, a patio restaurant on the second floor, and a dance bar on the second. The menu features delicious traditional cuisine accompanied by cocktails. An address not to be missed for an authentic Barbès ambience.

label: Le Chalet du Lac
comment: Le Chalet du Lac, the legendary venue that hosted the Sex Pistols' first Paris concert in 1976, is back in the ballroom spirit. Opened in 1904, it was completely restored in 2003 to its Belle Époque charm. This institution now organizes evenings and tea dances, with an emphasis on ballroom dancing. A real invitation to relive the festive, elegant atmosphere of yesteryear!

label: Métropole Grecque Orthodoxe
comment: Saint-Stéphane Greek Cathedral, near the Pont de l'Alma, is the headquarters of the Greek Orthodox Church of Paris. Inaugurated in December 1895, this Byzantine-style edifice is a historic monument of great beauty, with its gilded dome and remarkable interior frescoes. In addition to its aesthetic value, the cathedral is of major importance as the home of the Greek Orthodox Metropolitan of France, giving it a central role in the Orthodox religious community in France.

It also showcases works by emerging talents such as Fiona Rae, Martin Barré, Joana Vasconcelos and Rosson Crow. The address for art lovers: 18 rue du Bourg-Tibourg - 75004 Paris.

label: Fédération française de cuisine
comment: The Fédération française de cuisine and the Mairie de Paris are offering free cooking classes at Paris markets. No classrooms, just total immersion in the open air! For an hour, the chef and a group of 5 to 10 participants come together to share a convivial moment around fresh produce, attracting curious passers-by. An original way to learn how to cook while discovering the atmosphere of Parisian markets.

label: Théâtre Paris-Villette
comment: The Théâtre Paris Villette, nestled in the eponymous park, opened its doors in 1986 in a delightful 19th-century building. With its large 226-seat auditorium, it is the ideal place to discover contemporary creation. Its unique location and richly diverse program make it a cultural gem not to be missed.

label: Flora Danica
comment: The Flora Danica brasserie on the Champs-Élysées charms with its warm ambience and Scandinavian decor. Its large dining room and green marble bar make it the perfect place for lunch or dinner. Chefs Andreas Møller and Guillaume Leray offer an innovative cuisine that promises an exquisite culinary experience. Decorated by the GamFratesi agency, Flora Danica is a must-visit address thanks to its elegant, natural decor.

label: Le Loir dans la théière
comment: Located in the Marais district, rue des Rosiers, Le Loir dans la théière is renowned for its delicious home-made pastries. Gourmets love the scones, lemon tart and chocolate fondant. At weekends, the place is very popular for its brunch and attracts a long queue. Once seated in the comfortable armchairs, customers enjoy the warm ambience of this establishment to the full.

label: Église protestante unie de Paris Batignolles
comment: Located in a lively district of Paris, this Protestant temple stands out for its warm welcome to a varied clientele. Its architecture blends neo-Romanesque and modern features, while its bright interior and geometrically-patterned stained glass windows fascinate visitors. An open and inclusive place of worship, ideally integrated into the diversity of the City of Light.

label: American Concierge
comment: AmericanConcierge.com, launched in 2014, offers personalized itineraries to American travelers in France and the UK. Based in the U.S. and Paris, their team works closely with customers for unique experiences. With over 70 certified guides and a local team, they offer private tours, from the classic to the unusual, for half or full days. These bilingual guides guarantee enriching discoveries for a memorable stay.

label: Givenchy
comment: Givenchy embodies French chic with its haute couture creations, reflecting luxury and elegance. Audrey Hepburn, Hubert de Givenchy's muse, symbolizes the timeless elegance of the house. Her unique style has contributed to the brand's international success. Givenchy remains an undisputed benchmark of luxury and fashion, seducing lovers of authenticity and sophistication.

label: Elisa Guide Paris
comment: Discover Paris with experienced guide Elisa Jéhanno. Visit famous museums, typical neighborhoods and treasures of the Paris region. Take virtual tours by videoconference from 2020. Enjoy tailor-made tours for couples, families or friends. Immerse yourself in the history and art of Paris for an enriching and entertaining experience.

label: Piscine Georges Rigal
comment: Located close to the famous Père-Lachaise cemetery, the Georges Rigal swimming pool offers visitors two 12.50-meter pools. Swimming enthusiasts will find a wide range of activities on offer, including aquagym, aqua form and special sessions for baby swimmers. An ideal place to relax and work out in a friendly, dynamic environment.

label: Katmandou Café
comment: Located in the lively Bastille district, Katmandou Café is a charming Indian restaurant with a warm, authentic atmosphere. Its traditional decor creates a cosy, exotic atmosphere. The menu offers tasty, fragrant cuisine, a true invitation to culinary travel. An ideal place to discover or rediscover the delights of India in a friendly, welcoming atmosphere.

The menu offers tasty, fragrant cuisine, a true invitation to culinary travel. An ideal place to discover or rediscover the delights of India in a friendly, welcoming atmosphere.

label: Café de l'Ours
comment: Nestled in the heart of the Musée d'Orsay, the Café de l'Ours attracts visitors with its emblematic polar bear. Conviviality and simplicity are the hallmarks of this eatery. You can enjoy fresh salads, sandwiches, pastries, ice creams and pastries. Perfect for a break before resuming your visit to the museum's Impressionist art treasures. An unmissable place to indulge and recharge your batteries in a friendly atmosphere.

label: Lavoir Moderne Parisien
comment: A former 19th-century washhouse, this theater in the Goutte d'Or has been a genuine cultural venue since 1986. Oriented towards contemporary creation, it spotlights young authors and innovative forms of writing. Renowned artists include Joël Pommerat, Valère Novarina and Youssou N'Dour. A multi-disciplinary artistic space conducive to encounters and the expression of cultural diversity.

label: Marché Baudoyer
comment: The Baudoyer food market, nestled close to the Hôtel de Ville and on the edge of the Marais district, stands out as the first Parisian market to open its stalls in the afternoon. Some 15 merchants offer exceptional products: fish, fresh fruit and vegetables, cheese, poultry and a variety of flowers. A must for lovers of good food and quality products.

label: Le BAL
comment: Once the ballroom of the Roaring Twenties, this space is now dedicated to the representation of reality through images. Le Bal is an artistic platform showcasing the work of photographers, video artists and filmmakers who question the power of images. In addition to the exhibitions, debates and awareness-raising events are organized for the general public, especially young people, to reflect on the political and aesthetic issues raised by the works presented.

label: Stock Zadig & Voltaire
comment: Don't miss out on the best bargains with incredible reductions of up to -60% in this specialized boutique. Discover a wide selection of clothing and accessories from the brand with a unique style, between rock and girly. Take advantage of exceptional discounts ranging from -30% to -60% to treat yourself to fashionable pieces at unbeatable prices. Assert your personality with original, trendy clothes, and stand out with elegance!

label: Bouillon République
comment: Bouillon République, located near Place de la République, is a newcomer to the Parisian culinary scene. Its oysters for 1?, mayonnaise eggs for less than 2?, private dining rooms and takeaway/delivery service revisit the tradition of Parisian bouillons. Its setting, inspired by the brasseries of the 1930s and renovated by the Lafond firm, offers an authentic and convivial experience for lovers of French cuisine at a low price.

label: Séoul-Opéra
comment: Located near Place Vendôme, Séoul-Opéra offers exceptional Korean cuisine, expertly prepared using traditional techniques. A genuine invitation to discover the flavors of Korea, in a refined and convivial setting. A must for lovers of Asian gastronomy in search of authenticity and refinement.

label: A Mi-Chemin
comment: The A Mi-Chemin restaurant, founded by chef Nordine Labiadh, blends oriental delights with authentic French cuisine. In a warm setting, guests are transported by the flavors of the chef's childhood in Tunisia. Recognized as the Premier Couscous de Paris and the Deuxième de France in 2020, A Mi-Chemin also appeals to wine lovers with its natural, organic selection. A gourmet address that awakens the senses. (297 characters)

label: Studio 28
comment: Located on the Butte Montmartre, Studio 28 is an art-house cinema renowned for its screening of current films and great classics. Its garden bar offers a pleasant setting for relaxing before or after the screening. Prices are very attractive, making it an ideal destination for film buffs in search of enriching discoveries.

label: CSAO
comment: The SWAC is home to a veritable festival of African arts and crafts, bathing the space in bright colors and warm light. Objects, clothing and jewelry made in Africa stand side by side with unique works of art. On a regular basis, artists take over this spacious space to present temporary exhibitions, creating a veritable voyage to the heart of African creativity.

label: Grand Duc
comment: The Grand Duc restaurant, nestled in a former Eiffel-style jewelry workshop, is located in the Haut Marais district, close to the Carreau du Temple. As soon as you step inside, you discover a dining room with a traditional ambiance, a cocktail bar, and a wine bar with a selection of tapas, all under a superb glass roof on the top floor. An address combining elegance and conviviality for a unique culinary experience.

label: Eres (Saint-Germain-des-Prés)
comment: For forty years, the Eres brand has been a fashion benchmark with swimwear and lingerie collections that enhance the female body. Each piece combines timeless design and high-quality materials for optimum comfort. The sleek, refined and colorful creations enhance every woman's femininity with elegance. Thanks to its unique know-how, Eres seduces women all over the world with pieces that combine comfort and aesthetics.

label: Chez Shen
comment: Welcome to this Asian restaurant, where smiles are the order of the day, dishes are tasty and generous, and prices are very affordable. The cuisine is simple yet deliciously authentic. The portions are more than generous, enough to satisfy even the most demanding palates. A must-visit address for an exotic and tasty culinary experience at an affordable price.

label: Akrame
comment: Located close to Place de la Madeleine and the department stores, Akrame's chic, modern setting is a real draw. There's no menu here, just a choice of dishes. A tasting experience where you have to rely entirely on the chef to discover a creative and refined cuisine. An invitation to trust and discover flavors in elegant, contemporary surroundings.

label: Siamin
comment: Ideally located near the Champs-Élysées, this Thai restaurant offers an authentic Asian culinary experience. The dishes, prepared by talented chefs, are tasty and generous. The exotic setting invites you on a unique culinary journey. An experience to share with friends or family to discover the delights of Thai cuisine.

label: Angelina Musée du Luxembourg
comment: Discover for the first time on the Left Bank the timeless charm of a Parisian institution at the Musée du Luxembourg. Treat yourself to a unique moment as you sample the famous "l'Africain" hot chocolate and the legendary Mont-Blanc with chestnut cream. An unforgettable gourmet experience not to be missed during your visit.

label: EPMT - École de Paris des métiers de la table
comment: The École de Paris des Métiers de la Table, forges talent in cuisine, pastry-making and chocolate-making. Its La Fontaine application restaurant welcomes you Monday to Friday, from 12:30 to 2:30 pm, for a menu prepared by the students at a cost of 19?50, featuring traditional gastronomy in all its richness and authenticity.

label: Le Pavillon des Canaux
comment: This multifunctional pavilion offers a coffee shop, a coworking space and a meeting place. Its menu features soups, salads, pastries and homemade spreads prepared with quality products. It also hosts short film screenings, conferences, creative workshops, art exhibitions, tango demonstrations and concerts. A varied program to suit all tastes.

label: Auberge de Venise
comment: Enzo Volpe, chef at the Auberge de Venise since 1989, takes you on a journey to the heart of Italy with his emblematic dishes. From Ossobuco to Penne all'arrabiata and Spaghetti alle Vongole, Enzo invites you to discover authentic cuisine. With its creamy risottos and delicious Venetian-style veal liver, a unique experience awaits you at Enzo Volpe!

label: Librairie des Alpes
comment: The Librairie des Alpes, a veritable temple for mountain enthusiasts, houses an impressive collection of 10,000 old and new books, plus photos, engravings and magazines. It's an exceptional place where the works of famous mountaineers such as Roger Frison-Roche, Gaston Rebuffat and Bernard Pierre stand side by side. A goldmine for lovers of adventure and mountain literature.

label: Comédie Bastille
comment: Created in 1985 in a courtyard near the Bastille, the "Théâtre des Cinquante" became the "Comédie Bastille" in 2001. Since its inception, the theater has showcased new talent and offered a rich and varied program. In addition to its regular shows, the Comédie Bastille also offers performances in English for students, making it a must-see for entertainment fans.

label: Citéco
comment: The Citéco museum in Paris aims to make economics fun and accessible to all. Its varied program offers games, manipulations and interactive experiences for a better understanding of this discipline. Housed in a neo-Renaissance mansion, a former branch of the Banque de France, Citéco offers evening events, workshops and conferences. A must-see for anyone interested in economics.

label: Centre sportif Louis Lumière
comment: Located between the gates of Montreuil and Bagnolet, the Louis Lumière stadium offers a wide range of sports facilities. It features a soccer pitch, a 400-meter athletics track, as well as high jump and long jump tracks. Accessible and well-equipped, this stadium is an ideal place for sports and physical activities.

label: Ze Kitchen Galerie
comment: Ze Kitchen Gallery is an art gallery-restaurant offering original Asian-inspired cuisine. This unique venue combines gastronomy and contemporary art for a unique sensory experience. Michelin-starred chef William Ledeuil, passionate about Asia, will introduce you to creative and delicious dishes. Perfect for lovers of playful, refined cuisine, blending Western and Asian flavors, this atypical venue invites you to discover the culinary arts in a whole new way.

label: Wagon bleu
comment: The historic 1927 Orient-Express carriage from the Gare Saint-Lazare to Les Batignolles offers charm and distinction. Its period decor and retro ambience allow passengers to travel back in time while enjoying refined dishes. This train journey offers a unique experience combining tradition and modernity for an unforgettable moment along the rails of the capital. An invitation to a culinary and historical journey through picturesque landscapes.

label: Marché Port-Royal
comment: Close to the Val-de-Grâce hospital, the Port-Royal market is one of Paris's most convivial spots. With its many stalls of organic produce, it offers a delightful gustatory escapade for locals and visitors alike. An ideal rendezvous for lovers of fresh, local produce in a warm, authentic atmosphere.

label: Rolex
comment: Renowned for its high-quality watches, Rolex embodies elegance and refinement. Each piece reflects exceptional craftsmanship. The Place Vendôme boutique showcases the most prestigious creations. A Rolex watch is an investment in history and time. The brand's excellence is handed down from generation to generation, symbolized by its crowned logo, an emblem of luxury and sophistication.

label: Librairie La Musardine
comment: Every year, Librairie La Musardine offers a wide selection of erotic literature, from guidebooks to essays, encyclopedias and novels. Discover eroticism in all its forms, with works that are never vulgar. The famous "Osez" guides offer practical advice and answer all your questions about sexuality. Immerse yourself in this fascinating and instructive universe that will awaken your senses.

label: Piscine de la Butte-aux-Cailles
comment: Built in 1924, the Butte-aux-Cailles swimming pool features an imposing vault supported by concrete arches. Its art nouveau architecture blends perfectly with the picturesque charm of the neighborhood. Ranked as one of the two most emblematic swimming pools in Paris, the Butte-aux-Cailles offers three pools - a 33m, a 25m and a smaller 12m - as well as a unique outdoor Nordic pool, accessible all year round. An aquatic nugget in the heart of the capital!

label: Piscine Aspirant Dunand
comment: The Aspirant Dunand pool, near the Catacombes de Paris, offers an oasis of calm in the heart of the city. With its 25-meter pool, it's perfect for swimmers in search of relaxation. In addition to swimming, aquatic activities such as aquagym keep you fit and having fun. Whether for sport or relaxation, this pool is the ideal place to escape urban stress and enjoy a moment of peace and quiet.

label: Eberhardt Livestore
comment: Located near the Viaduc des Arts, the Eberhardt Live Store is an exclusive showroom for three high-end brands: Liebherr, Falmec and Asko. In a welcoming 200m² space, you'll discover a wide selection of appliances: refrigerators, freezers, wine cellars, stoves, washing machines and hoods. Immerse yourself in the world of quality appliances, where comfort and performance are paramount.

label: Akira Back
comment: Internationally-renowned chef Akira Back, a Red Guide award-winner, sets up shop on Avenue George V in Paris. For the first time in Europe, he unveils his culinary savoir-faire to Parisians and travelers from all over the world. In an elegant setting, his restaurant offers modern Japanese cuisine with an international flair, providing a unique and refined gastronomic experience.

label: Centre sportif Charles Moureu
comment: At the heart of the Olympiades district lies the Charles Moreu sports center, with its athletics track and welcoming outdoor spaces for sports enthusiasts. In addition to individual activities, the center offers contemporary dance, dance initiation and dance initiation classes for budding dance enthusiasts. A dynamic and accessible place to work out and have fun in a friendly atmosphere.

label: Musée des Plans-reliefs - Hôtel national des Invalides
comment: The Musée des plans-reliefs exhibits historical models of fortified towns from Louis XIV to Napoleon III. These plans, tools of military planning and symbols of power, are now invaluable teaching aids. Visitors can admire these models, which offer an aerial view of the towns, their buildings and ramparts, as well as the surrounding landscape. Multimedia terminals with virtual reality and 3D modeling for total immersion.

The terrace is ideal for relaxing after shopping, a pleasure break in the city.

label: Galerie Templon Paris
comment: Founded in 1966 by the famous art gallerist of the same name, Galerie Templon Paris is an emblematic venue for French contemporary art. Collaborating with some forty visual artists, it has welcomed such major figures as Jean-Michel Basquiat, César, Keith Haring and Andy Warhol. The gallery now has two spaces in Paris and another in Brussels, reinforcing its international reputation.

Its varied program includes some 170 performances a year, from rock to variety, one-man/woman shows and entertainment. The biggest stars shine here.

label: Consignes dans les gares et les parcs de loisirs
comment: Paris's major train stations offer lockers from 5.50? for 24 hours. Available at Gare de l'Est (8am-8pm), Gare de Lyon (6.15am-10pm), Gare Montparnasse (7am-11pm), Gare du Nord (6am-11.15pm), Gare d'Austerlitz (6am-10pm), Marne-la-Vallée - Chessy (7am-10pm), Aéroport CDG 2 TGV (6am-9.30pm), Parc Disneyland (8am-45min after closing time) and Parc Walt Disney Studio (10am-5pm). Rates: 3? small, 7? medium Avoid valuables in the lockers.

label: Musée d’Ennery
comment: In 1894, Clémence d'Ennery donated her collection of Far Eastern art to the French state. Nicknamed the "menagerie of fantasy", it comprises 7,000 objects reflecting the life and beliefs of China and Japan between the 16th and 19th centuries. These treasures are displayed in a Second Empire mansion, with marquetry and mother-of-pearl showcases. A visit to this museum is well worthwhile for its unique atmosphere.

label: Musée Cognacq-Jay
comment: The Musée Cognacq-Jay, in the Marais district of Paris, plunges us into the atmosphere of the Age of Enlightenment. Housed in a 16th-century mansion, it displays 18th-century treasures: paintings by Boucher, Chardin and Fragonard, sketches by Watteau, sculptures, furniture, jewelry and Saxon porcelain. Donated to Paris in 1928, these fascinating collections offer a total immersion in the art and history of the period.

Discover French burger excellence at Blend!

label: Oh My God She’s Parisian!
comment: Don't miss Julie Collas's new show, "Oh My God She's Parisian!", which has already won over 25,000 spectators. Whether you've seen it or not, go and see it! Even in English, anyone from 15 to 80 can understand this bubbly Frenchwoman. In this show full of improvisation, singing and mime, Julie takes you through a typical Parisian day, revealing the (good) habits of the capital. A not-to-be-missed experience for all Paris lovers!

label: Maison-atelier du peintre Amédée Ozenfant
comment: Villa Reille, also known as Maison Ozenfant, is an iconic residence designed by architect Le Corbusier in 1922 for painter Amédée Ozenfant. Located on the corner of avenue Reille and square Montsouris, this modern house features a sleek white facade with large skylights. Amédée Ozenfant occupied the first-floor apartment, while his luminous studio was located on the second floor. Remarkable architecture not to be missed!

It's up to you to create a look that suits you by juggling these two distinct universes.

label: Maison Paris Nature
comment: The Maison Paris Nature raises Parisians' awareness of the need to preserve the capital's biodiversity. Its Nature Library, in the Parc Floral du Bois de Vincennes, organizes meetings, activities and workshops led by passionate advisors. They also meet the public in the butterfly, Pierre Emmanuel and Saint-Vincent gardens to offer advice and share their love of Paris's wild nature.

The few tables in this place steeped in history remain highly sought-after, testifying to its timeless charm. A place not to be missed for enjoying the heady atmosphere of Montmartre.

comment: The Espace Sportif Pailleron, managed by the City of Paris, is a must for fitness enthusiasts. With a 33 x 15-metre swimming pool and an 800 m² ice rink, there's something for everyone. The swimming pool, a listed historic monument, offers a unique setting with its bay window and glass roof. A fun aquatic area, solarium and equipped rooms are also available. At Pailleron, there's something for everyone!

label: Église réformée de l'Oratoire du Louvre
comment: The former church of this Catholic religious order, now a temple, illustrates the proliferation of congregations in 17th-century Paris. Its revolutionary architecture stands out from traditional churches, with its double ambulatory. Don't miss the neo-classical organ dating from the 1930s, which graces the interior of this magnificent edifice.
