Every mouthful and every glass transports you into an atmosphere rich in flavors, perfect for reunions with friends or family. A must for food and wine lovers in search of authentic French cuisine.

comment: The Personal Shopper is much more than just a fashion expert, he's a connoisseur of brands, products, prices and Parisian boutiques. Using his services transforms your approach to fashion. As your private stylist, he'll guide you in your choice of outfits that suit you. The Personal Shopper offers you a tailor-made service and personalized support for successful fashion shopping every time.

label: Evasion Verte
comment: The Évasion Verte accrobranche course, located in the heart of the Parc Floral near the Château de Vincennes, offers 60 workshops spread over 4 courses. At heights ranging from 1.5m to 12m, test your agility on Himalayan bridges, tightrope walkers, barrels and zip lines. Swings add a playful touch for young and old (6 years and up). Enjoy a day full of thrills and laughter with family, friends or groups in Paris, in an exceptional setting!

label: Paroisse Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre
comment: Nestled in Square René Viviani, Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre church is an ancient Parisian gem, dating back to the 12th century. Built on 6th-century remains, it boasts capitals, a 1900 Byzantine iconostasis and a relic of the Roman road linking Lutetia to Orleans. Outside, the imposing 12th-century buttresses catch the eye. Since 1889, the church has been home to the faithful of the Melchite Greek Catholic Church, and resounds with classical music concerts.

This hybrid of bar and bistro welcomes you to a warm setting where authentic French cuisine blends with modern touches. The relaxed, friendly atmosphere and brocante-style decor add a touch of originality to this must-visit address for food lovers.

label: Lenôtre – Boutiques parisiennes
comment: At Lenôtre, takeaway gastronomy is a must, 7 days a week. You'll find viennoiseries, hand-crafted chocolates, festive menus, delicatessen, wines and champagnes selected by Olivier Poussier, World's Best Sommelier 2000, as well as Lenôtre's famous pastries. Not forgetting gourmet gifts, confectionery, marrons glacés, petits fours, macaroons and other delights to be discovered in store. Exquisite flavours to delight every palate!

label: Fondation GoodPlanet - Domaine de Longchamp
comment: Nestled between Longchamp and Bagatelle, this estate offers a spectacular green setting. The château and its 13th-century tower are historical treasures. Occupied by the GoodPlanet Foundation since 2005, the site has become a center for ecological awareness. Exhibitions, debates, concerts, screenings and a collection of world musical instruments are planned to educate the public about environmental preservation. An exemplary initiative for our planet.

label: The Joke Comedy Club
comment: Discover The Joke, a Comedy Club where luxury and humor meet for a premium stand-up experience. Talent like Lecaplain and Mirabel rock our stages. Come and laugh every night in sumptuous surroundings.

label: K. Jacques
comment: Since 1933, K.Jacques de Saint-Tropez sandals have captured the hearts of celebrities. This family-owned brand excels in craftsmanship to offer sandal models ranging from the simplest to the most sophisticated. The key to their success lies in traditional craftsmanship that guarantees their unrivalled durability and quality. A must for lovers of fashion and timeless style.

label: Kimonoya
comment: In the heart of Kimonoya, a haven dedicated to the richness of Japanese culture, artisan treasures of unparalleled finesse flourish. Fans, lanterns, crockery, fabrics, teapots and even calligraphy materials come together in an intoxicating dance of beauty and elegance. Each object found in this fascinating universe embodies the very essence of Japanese delicacy.

label: Higuma
comment: This very popular establishment on Rue Sainte-Anne attracts an enthusiastic crowd. There's no sushi or sashimi here, just simple, convivial Japanese dishes. Enjoy a lamen or udon soup at the counter as you watch the chefs. Enjoy a katsudon, breaded pork cutlet on a bed of onions, or opt for a noodle stir-fry. Welcome to Rue Sainte-Anne's most popular Japanese cantine.

label: Marins de Paris "Zeus"
comment: Embark on a private cruise on the Seine with Marins de Paris! From 1 to 12 people, enjoy an exclusive cruise departing from the Port de l'Arsenal in the Bastille district. With complimentary drinks, choose the time that suits you best for a romantic getaway or a party with friends. Opt for breakfast, lunch or dinner on board for an unforgettable experience in the heart of the capital. Experience an enchanted interlude on the waves of Paris with Marins de Paris.

label: Pain de sucre
comment: Pain de Sucre collections celebrate well-being and escape, with sun-kissed swimwear that enhances the feminine silhouette. In addition to swimwear, the brand also offers refined lingerie, tops, dresses and pareos to complete your summer wardrobe with style and elegance. Enjoy a touch of exoticism and sensuality with pieces from this collection that will transport you straight to the tropics.

label: Make my D
comment: Discover a promising shopping escapade at Nathalie Bui, Barbara's sister. Prepare yourself for a day enchanted by an exquisite range of jeans (Acquaverde, Renhsen), t-shirts (Fine collection, Little Marcel), trendy dresses (Margit Brandt) and refined accessories. A shopping experience that's sure to brighten up your day!

label: Es
comment: Restaurant Es, located in the 7th arrondissement of Paris, offers a hushed, sophisticated ambience that appeals to lovers of good food. The menu features French cuisine revisited, with subtly crafted, deliciously savory dishes. Each plate is a true work of art, combining flavors and textures with finesse. Es is a must for an unforgettable gastronomic experience in Paris.

label: Galerie Lacroix
comment: The urban and geek art gallery features artists such as Arkiv Vilmansa from Indonesia, Ajee and Grégoire 'Léon' Guillemin from France, and Unwell Bunny from Australia. Their creations are inspired by the pop worlds of comics, manga and heroic fantasy, offering aesthetically rich works that blend humor and strangeness. Through their art, these artists question contemporary society. A cultural melting pot that captivates with its diversity and originality.

label: Le Penty
comment: Discover Kémia, an assortment of appetizers to enjoy as an aperitif! Made with spicy potatoes, piquant olives and caraway beans, this specialty is offered with every drink ordered at Le Penty, a friendly bar near Place d'Aligre. The warm ambience and inviting terrace make this the ideal place to enjoy a summer aperitif on a budget. A tasty experience not to be missed!

label: Théâtre de la Porte Saint-Martin
comment: Since its opening in 1781, the Théâtre de la Porte Saint-Martin has welcomed famous French artists such as Alexandre Dumas, Victor Hugo, Sarah Bernhardt and Louis de Funès. Plays such as Cyrano de Bergerac and Les Misérables have been performed here, with actors including Christian Clavier and Didier Bourdon. The 1050-seat theater is a landmark on the French theatre scene.

label: Jardin de Sans Souci
comment: Discover the pleasure of savoring Chinese dishes in the open air, comfortably seated under an elegant plant balustrade. Let yourself be carried away by the delights of Asian cuisine while enjoying the relaxing ambience of a shaded terrace. A gourmet and soothing experience that will satisfy your taste buds and offer you an unforgettable moment of relaxation.

label: Marian Goodman Gallery
comment: The renowned Marian Goodman gallery moved to the Marais in 1999, following the success of its first space in New York. A major figure in Parisian art, it represents renowned artists such as Giuseppe Penone, Gerhard Richter, Christian Boltanski and Annette Messager. Her international influence was confirmed with the opening of a space in London in 2014.

label: Guide Martin Ziemann
comment: I've been an experienced tour leader and guide since 1990, and I'm here to help you discover Paris in a personalized way. Whether you're a family or a group, I'll adapt to your needs to create a customized program. Contact me in advance to work out together a program that will give you a complete overview of the capital and its fascinating history.

label: The Ways Beyond
comment: Discover Paris in a different way with TheWaysBeyond, specialists in unique cultural experiences in the Paris region. Founded by two Paris enthusiasts, this initiative offers authentic discoveries far removed from tourist clichés. Explore the City of Light through the eyes of its inhabitants, meeting inspiring artists, craftspeople, chefs and designers. TheWaysBeyond, for a total immersion in Parisian creativity.

label: Panasia
comment: Located in the heart of the Îlot Panoramic in the Beaugrenelle shopping center, the Panasia restaurant offers a unique culinary journey close to the Eiffel Tower. Fusing the emblematic flavors of the Far East, it offers a cuisine blending Chinese, Japanese, Korean, Vietnamese, Thai, Cambodian and Indonesian influences. An immersion in the delights of Asia, in an exotic and refined setting.

label: Chloé
comment: Chloé sublimates femininity through noble materials such as cashmere, silk twill, satin, leather and tweed. The combination of these quality fabrics with borrowings from the men's wardrobe lends each piece a nonchalant, timeless elegance. A subtle harmony between refinement and casualness that characterizes the sophisticated universe of the Chloé brand.

label: She's cake by Séphora Saada
comment: Séphora Saada, talented pastry chef, reinvents the cheesecake, an emblem of American gastronomy. Her surprising creations, true conceptual works, are presented like fashion collections, changing with the seasons. The ultimate in originality, savoury versions of the famous dessert are also available, to the delight of gourmets in search of innovation.

label: Pauline Pô
comment: Immerse yourself in the enchanting world of Pauline Pô and let yourself be enchanted by her unique creations: dresses, skirts, tops, tunics, coats and much more. With a touch of '20s madness and a romantic, pop, sexy or fairy-tale inspiration, each piece is a work of art in its own right. Accessorize your outfit with bonnets, flowers, scarves and jewelry for a look that's both sophisticated and original.

label: Bibliothèque Nationale de France - Site François Mitterrand
comment: The BnF holds over 40 million documents spanning five centuries, covering a wide range of artistic and intellectual fields. Sites such as François-Mitterrand, Richelieu, Arsenal and Opéra offer reading and research facilities. Exhibitions, readings, conferences and concerts are also organized. The François-Mitterrand site offers 200 cultural events a year to introduce the public to its treasures.

Appreciated for its warm, relaxed atmosphere, as well as its attractive prices, this establishment has become a must for anyone looking for a convivial place to relax.

comment: H&M stores position themselves as fashion leaders, offering trendy clothes designed in collaboration with renowned designers, all at affordable prices. Their innovative concept combines quality, style and affordability, appealing to a broad customer base in search of original, fashionable pieces without breaking the bank. H&M has established itself as an essential reference for those who want to be at the cutting edge of fashion without compromising their budget.

A touch of glamour and sophistication that gives every woman the opportunity to shine like Audrey Hepburn in the iconic film.

label: Lina's - Place des Victoires
comment: Since 1989, Lina's has been offering "beautiful sandwiches" to make your own, with the finest ingredients for unique flavors. Flexibility, fresh salads and local produce are all available. For a quick breakfast, lunch with friends or a gourmet snack, Lina's caters to all culinary tastes. To eat in or take away. A must for gourmets in search of unique taste sensations, Lina's awaits you to discover this little corner of paradise.

label: La Bellevilloise
comment: Founded in 1877, La Bellevilloise is a house dedicated to light and creation. Spread over 2000m² on 4 floors, this cultural venue in Paris offers a variety of events: concerts, exhibitions, debates, a market, a club and a café-restaurant. Nestled in the former Maison du Peuple, La Bellevilloise offers a space for all forms of expression. Open to all, this magical place is an architectural heritage to be discovered, a place for encounters and discoveries.

label: Musée Carnavalet - Histoire de Paris
comment: The Musée Carnavalet, in the Marais district, traces the history of Paris from its earliest days. Founded in 1880, it is housed in two private mansions dating from the 16th and 17th centuries. Discover archaeological treasures, medieval relics, objects from the French Revolution, works of art and furniture, presented in rooms recreating the atmosphere of Parisian homes from the 15th to the 19th centuries. Don't forget the orangery, renovated in 2000, and the temporary exhibitions for a fascinating journey through the history of Paris!

comment: The Gaîté Montparnasse theater, in the heart of the eponymous district, boasts a rich artistic program. From comedies to classics and musicals, it offers a diverse range of performances every week. Nestled in the lively rue de la Gaîté, it's a must-see for Parisian culture lovers in search of quality entertainment.

label: Wecandoo
comment: Discover a world of authentic craftsmanship by taking part in a workshop with an artisan! Become a leatherworker, cabinetmaker, jeweler, cheesemaker, ceramist or baker for the duration of a session. With Wecandoo, choose from over 2,000 passionate craftsmen ready to pass on their know-how and guide you in the creation of a unique piece. Immerse yourself in the art of the handmade and share a special moment with these Made In France talents!

label: M.A.C.
comment: M.A.C., for Makeup Artist Cosmetics, has several boutiques in Paris, as well as space in department stores. Originally reserved for professionals, their products are now accessible to all. They offer a wide choice of products to enhance your appearance, as well as accessories to enhance your make-up. Teams of specialists are on hand to offer advice and, why not, a make-up session by renowned artists?

label: La Ruche - Cité d'artistes
comment: La Ruche, founded in 1900 by sculptor Alfred Boucher, is an emblematic place where some 50 artists work. Its renowned residents include Fernand Léger, Chaïm Soutine, Zadkine, Marc Chagall and Blaise Cendrars. Its listed facades and roofs bear witness to its architectural heritage dating back to the 1900 Universal Exhibition. A true creative space, La Ruche is only open to visitors on special occasions.

label: Rex Studios
comment: Discover Europe's largest cinema in an interactive and cultural way! Take a behind-the-scenes look at the 7th Art through emblematic sets such as the projection booth and the film set. Immerse yourself in the history of cinema and a French heritage monument since 1932. The tour is suitable for school groups, leisure centers and works councils, with an audio-guided tour for children aged 5 and over. Don't miss this unique cinematic experience at Rex Studios!

label: Mansouria
comment: Mansouria, an oriental-style restaurant in the heart of Paris, plunges you into a world of exotic delights. Launched in 1985 by Fatema Hal, a Moroccan cuisine enthusiast, the establishment is renowned for its refined dishes such as the succulent Pastilla with pigeon and the delicious Mourouzia, dating back to the 12th century. Located close to the Bastille, Mansouria also offers a wide selection of couscous and tagines for an unforgettable taste experience.

label: La Danse de la fontaine émergente
comment: Installed in Paris Rive Gauche, La danse de la fontaine émergente is a work by artist Chen Zhen. The sculpture depicts a dragon emerging from an underground factory. Its glass, metal and stainless steel structure reveals the water circulating under pressure. Commissioned by Paris, it was unveiled in 2008 and remains a monumental work illuminated at night.

label: Rue France
comment: Discover a fascinating world of antiques: small trinkets, crockery, old books, postcards, paintings, engravings, frames, mirrors, typewriters, vinyl records, lighting, bronzes, advertising, military, folk art and garden objects, as well as small pieces of furniture from the Art Deco, 50s and 70s periods, and industrial furniture. A diversity of authentic objects that will appeal to lovers of rare and singular pieces.

label: Café des Phares
comment: The Café des Phares, located on the Place de la Bastille, is renowned as the pioneer of philosophical cafés in France. Every Sunday morning, it hosts lively debates open to all, offering an exciting forum for exchange and discussion on a variety of subjects. A must for lovers of reflection and enriching discussions.

label: Les Catacombes de Paris
comment: The Catacombs, with their six million bones spread over 11,000 m², offer a fascinating and mysterious experience. The 1.7 km-long galleries, situated at 1.80 m under vaulted ceilings, create a singular atmosphere at 14 degrees Celsius. This tour is not recommended for people with sensitive heart or respiratory systems, or for unaccompanied children. An unusual dive into the history of Paris, to be discovered at 36 rue Rémy Dumoncel for those in search of an underground adventure.

label: Dilia

Steeped in his Tuscan roots, the chef offers a bold Italian cuisine that will delight the taste buds of gourmets in search of authenticity and innovative flavors.

label: Théâtre de Paris
comment: The Théâtre de Paris, an emblematic venue of the French artistic scene in the heart of the capital, was founded at the end of the 18th century. Hosting some of the world's greatest theatrical talents, it offers a unique experience in its Salle Réjane. Richly humorous plays are programmed for unforgettable moments of entertainment. A must-see address for theater lovers in Paris.

A unique culinary experience to discover without delay.

label: Breakfast In America - Left Bank
comment: Opt for an American-style breakfast to get your day off to a great start! This typically American concept is distinguished by its abundance and diversity. Fluffy pancakes, crispy bacon, scrambled eggs, fresh fruit, everything to satisfy your taste buds. And don't forget the coffee or orange juice to accompany this morning feast. A real treat for lovers of hearty, gourmet breakfasts!

A real treat for lovers of hearty, gourmet breakfasts!

label: Bonpoint
comment: Discover Bonpoint's high-end collection of clothing, shoes and accessories for children aged 0 to 14. Made from noble materials, these garments bring a touch of chic and elegance to little ones. The boutique, housed in a private mansion with a 1,000 m² concept store, offers eight different universes as well as a French garden and tea room for a unique shopping experience.

label: Église Saint-Gervais Saint-Protais
comment: The Marais church, somewhere between Gothic and Classical, fascinates with its blend of styles. The 16th-century flamboyant Gothic nave contrasts with the classical façade, a jewel of the following century. The interior is sumptuously decorated, with a stone crown adorning the keystone of the Virgin Chapel. The stained glass windows in the Chapel of St. John the Baptist, dating from 1531, depict the Wisdom of Solomon. An architectural treasure trove for history and art lovers!

label: Librairie-boutique du musée Picasso-Paris
comment: The Musée National Picasso - Paris boutique-bookshop recreates the ambience of an artist's studio, with its parquet flooring, beams and wood and metal shelving. Each area, from textiles to tableware, including the studio-desk and children's area, invites you to wander peacefully. The bookshop offers a wide selection of works on Picasso and modern art, making it a lively place where artists and creators rub shoulders for a unique experience for art lovers.

label: Stella Forest
comment: Stella Forest skilfully blends different styles for unique garments, combining classic romanticism and bohemian ethnicity, modernity and retro. Original collections feature colorful embroideries and prints, adding freshness and whimsy. Bold and refined, the brand seduces women in search of style with singular, elegant outfits. Stella Forest offers looks full of character, a true invitation to originality.

label: Anahi
comment: Come and discover the most surprising Argentinian table in Paris, nestled in a former butcher's shop with a shaky front. A true paradise for lovers of South American meats and wines. An address not to be missed, which will delight your taste buds and take you on an authentic and delicious culinary journey.

label: Croccante
comment: Discover this Sicilian delicatessen, a veritable gourmet canteen offering a delicious variety of antipasti, fresh pastas, marinated vegetables, cold meats, cheeses and typical Sicilian desserts. A tempting choice that will delight lovers of authentic Italian cuisine. Immerse yourself in a unique, tasty culinary experience full of Sicilian traditions.

label: Marché couvert Saint-Martin
comment: Originally built in 1859 and renovated in 1880, the Saint-Martin covered market proudly displays its characteristic Baltard-style architecture. Inside, visitors can enjoy a variety of shops, including a Moroccan restaurant, an organic grocery store and catering stalls. A warm, lively atmosphere reigns here, inviting you to enjoy a pleasant gourmet stroll.

label: Benkay
comment: Benkay, a prestigious Japanese restaurant in the 15th arrondissement, boasts a breathtaking view over the Seine. Pots and pans in hand, our Japanese chefs, experts in washoku, traditional Japanese cuisine, concoct exceptional dishes before your astonished eyes. From succulent teriyaki beef to delicately prepared sushi and teppanyaki on a hot plate, Japanese gastronomy invites itself onto your plate for an unparalleled culinary experience.

label: Musée en herbe
comment: Since 1975, the Musée en Herbe in Paris has been offering art exhibitions for all ages, from 3 to 103. With renowned exhibitions and immersive tours, all visitors become the heroes of a captivating adventure. This intergenerational space offers a variety of cultural discoveries, activities, events, workshops for all ages, and a space dedicated to contemporary artists. Accessibility for all, including the disabled, is a priority for the Musée en Herbe.

label: Musée du Louvre
comment: Once the palace of the kings of France, the Louvre became a museum in 1793. Its prestigious collections span millennia and an immense territory. Eight departments, from Egyptian Antiquities to Byzantine Art, Paintings, Sculptures and Islamic Art, present nearly 33,000 exceptional works. A ninth department, Arts of Byzantium and Eastern Christianity, will enrich this cultural nugget by 2025.

additional_information: ['The Musée du Louvre is open daily, 9am-6pm, except Tuesdays. Nocturne until 9pm on Wednesdays and Fridays. Free admission on the 1st Friday of the month (except July and August). Entrance to the museum is via the Pyramid for individuals; Richelieu access is reserved for groups and Louvre loyalty cardholders.']

label: Musée Jacquemart-André
comment: The Musée Jacquemart-André at the Institut de France, compared to the Frick Collection in New York, impresses with its artistic wealth. The former home of Edouard André and Nélie Jacquemart, it offers a 19th-century immersion through its sumptuous salons, majestic staircase and winter garden. Visitors can admire art treasures from various regions, including Flemish and German works, frescoes and refined furniture.

label: Bibliothèque Nationale de France - Arsenal
comment: In 1757, François I's Arsenal, rebuilt by Sully, housed the Marquis de Paulmy's collection, including medieval manuscripts and prints. In 1797, this collection was made public and became part of the Bibliothèque nationale in 1934. Manuscripts, scores, old magazines and over 7,000 volumes are freely accessible. Exhibitions and literary evenings allow visitors to discover its treasures and beautiful antique woodwork. A wealth of culture to explore.

label: Musée des égouts de Paris
comment: The Paris Sewer Museum plunges visitors into the heart of the city's sewer system. Learn about the history and professions involved in sewerage, as well as environmental issues. Then set off to discover the network in action, to observe the water bodies and galleries, and better understand how they work and their importance for public health and the environment. An educational experience combining history, technology and the environment.

label: Ines de la Fressange
comment: A symbol of French elegance, Ines de la Fressange opened her boutique in May 2015, offering a unique venue in Saint-Germain-des-Prés. In this charming 200 m² space, blending atelier style and glass roof, the designer unveils her original collections, as well as treasures unearthed by herself. A must-see address for fashion lovers, where everyone can find the rare gem, whatever their budget.

label: Hôtel du Nord
comment: The owners of the Hôtel du Nord in Paris have set their sights on revitalizing this iconic venue! Part cinema, part bistro, the timeless ambience seduces diners who enjoy authentic brasserie cuisine along the Canal Saint-Martin. A festive place offering regular cabaret evenings for an unforgettable experience!

label: Samaritaine Paris Pont-Neuf - Visites guidées
comment: Come and discover La Samaritaine, a Paris landmark that has been steeped in a unique atmosphere for over 150 years. A symbol of a creative and spontaneous spirit, La Samaritaine captivates with its inimitable charm. After 16 years of closure, the heart of this mythical place beats again, offering Parisian visitors the opportunity to savor this French art de vivre in famous buildings linking the rue de Rivoli to the Pont-Neuf. Don't miss this unforgettable experience!

label: Sandro
comment: Talented fashion designer Évelyne Chetrite elegantly captures women's deepest desires with romantic, bohemian collections in tune with current trends. Following her success with women, she has now launched a new, bold and innovative line for men. Her creativity and sense of trends make her a key figure capable of reinventing dress codes to satisfy her public.

comment: Located close to the gateway to the Vanves flea market, the boulevard Brune food market is a must. Open every Thursday from 7 a.m. to 1 p.m. and Sunday mornings from 7 a.m. to 2.30 p.m., it offers a wide range of fresh, quality produce. A must for lovers of good food and local, artisanal products.

label: Hôtel de Beauvais
comment: The 17th-century Hôtel de Beauvais houses the Paris Administrative Court of Appeal. Its "Grand Style" architecture is particularly appealing, with its facade and imposing balcony. Don't miss the inner courtyard with its concave facades and the vestibule supported by 8 Doric columns. Visited by Louis XIV and Mozart, the building is open to visitors during the European Heritage Days. On weekdays, you can ask the janitor to let you admire its splendor.

label: Esthetic Center
comment: Esthetic Center makes beauty accessible to all with its 3 Parisian institutes open without appointment. Inexpensive treatments to suit all schedules, from hair removal to slimming cures. And for the lucky ones, happy hours are also available. Taking care of yourself has never been easier or more affordable.

Don't miss this unique opportunity to renew your wardrobe in style without breaking the bank!

label: Le Moulin de Longchamp
comment: Built in 1312 as part of the Abbey of Longchamp by Isabelle de France, the Moulin de Rouvray survived the destruction of the abbey in 1795. Used to pump water from the lakes, it was replaced by a stone tower mill in the 19th century. Located next to the Longchamp racecourse, it remains a fascinating historical landmark, although not open to the public.

label: Maison Margiela
comment: The Belgian designer's minimalist, avant-garde boutique is the perfect reflection of his collections for men and women. White-painted salvaged objects harmoniously furnish the space, highlighting the unstructured garments made from noble materials. A sober yet sophisticated atmosphere where every detail contributes to creating a unique experience for fashion lovers.

label: Le Calbar
comment: At Calbar, the waiters adopt a casual style with boxer shorts, suspenders and a butterfly bow tie. This unique cocktail bar blends a luxurious atmosphere with the art of mixology. In addition to drinks, customers can enjoy a gourmet club sandwich. Ideally located between Bastille and Gare de Lyon, this unusual venue even offers monthly aperitifs in boxer shorts for a convivial and original experience.

label: Café de la Gare
comment: Founded in 1969, the Café de la Gare, located in the Marais district, has become a landmark on the Parisian comedy scene. With 300 seats, this theater has welcomed the greatest comedians such as Coluche, Gérard Depardieu and Benoît Poelvoorde. A veritable temple of laughter, it has been a mainstay of the Paris comedy scene for generations. Its friendly atmosphere and history make it a mecca for French comedy, attracting audiences in search of entertainment and good humor.

comment: Close to the Place de la Bastille, the Centre des Arts Vivants offers a variety of dance, music and theater courses. The diversity of dance classes is remarkable: tap, contemporary, oriental, jazz, urban, flamenco, hip-hop, modern'jazz, pole dance, Argentine tango, salsa... A real boon for enthusiasts of all artistic disciplines.

label: Il Brigante
comment: Come and enjoy generous, tasty pizzas, prepared before your very eyes by an expert Calabrian pizzaiolo. Local Italian produce and crispy dough make every bite a pure delight. And if you're in a hurry, don't worry, you can take them away too! A festival of flavors to discover and savor without delay.

label: Big Bus Paris - Stop: Arc de Triomphe
comment: Big Bus' double-decker bus tours are the perfect way to discover Paris. Passengers hop on and off the bus as they please. One is immersed in the history, culture and architecture of Paris with commentary - informative and entertaining - available in 11 languages. From the buses' upper deck, you can admire the iconic Parisian monuments.

label: Église réformée du Marais
comment: The Temple du Marais, an emblematic church in the Marais district of Paris, captivates visitors with its remarkable architecture. Designed by architect François Mansart in 1632, it was inspired by the Pantheon in Rome. Its rotunda, 13.50 metres in diameter, is a real eye-catcher. Transformed into a Protestant temple in 1802, this historic monument bears witness to the turbulent history of Paris. A visit is a must to discover this architectural jewel steeped in spirituality.

comment: Nestled at the foot of the Montparnasse Tower, the Théâtre Le Guichet enjoys a privileged location in the hustle and bustle of the district. This small neighborhood theater stands out for its varied and original programming, featuring original texts and promising young companies. A vibrant place where creativity, passion and artistic discovery come together.

label: Maison Auguste Comte
comment: Auguste Comte, a major figure in 19th-century philosophy and instigator of positivism, once took refuge in this house, which was his final resting place in 1857. Now transformed into a museum dedicated to his life and work, the Maison d'Auguste Comte also houses a philosophical research center. Come and plunge into the heart of "positive philosophy" and discover the legacy left by this great thinker.

label: Loulou Paris
comment: Overlooking the Carrousel du Louvre, Restaurant Loulou, located in the Musée des Arts Décoratifs, offers a breathtaking view of Paris. From the Louvre Pyramid to the Eiffel Tower, the panorama is breathtaking. Guests can savor refined, flavorful Mediterranean cuisine in a chic, elegant setting designed by architect Joseph Dirand. A unique gastronomic experience in the heart of the City of Light.

label: Iconik Paris
comment: Right in the heart of the Italie Deux shopping center, in the dynamic 13th arrondissement of Paris, nestles Iconik Paris, an atypical venue. Its food court is packed with street food kiosks, its bar hosts lively afterworks and its weekly program includes DJ sets, karaoke and retro video game tournaments. Iconik Paris promises unique and memorable experiences in a pop atmosphere. Not to be missed!

label: Viality Tour
comment: Immerse yourself in the history of the Eiffel Tower with VIALITY TOUR in Paris. Accompanied by a guide and an assistant, set off from the École Militaire to reach the Eiffel Tower via the Champ-de-Mars. Relive its creation with a virtual reality headset at several stops. Attend its inauguration in 1889 for a unique, immersive experience you won't want to miss!

label: Les Étoiles
comment: Immerse yourself in the electric ambience of the Théâtre des Étoiles, a nugget of the cosmopolitan district. Founded in 1876, this atypical club offers a diverse program, from techno to electro and American hip-hop. Thanks to Live Nation, it is now transformed into a concert hall, event space and creative hub. Come and enjoy a unique experience in the heart of this place that has risen from the ashes, ready to enchant you.

label: Bois de Boulogne
comment: The wooded Parc de Boulogne, a former royal estate, is a popular destination west of Paris. With its 850 hectares including the Parc de Bagatelle, the Jardin des Serres d'Auteuil, the Pré-Catelan and the Jardin d'Acclimatation, it offers a wide range of activities: 28 km of paths, bridle paths, 15 km of cycle routes, playgrounds, Musée en Herbe, picnic areas, bike and boat hire, horse racing, restaurants and open-air theater. A true paradise for nature and leisure lovers.

The Jardin d'Acclimatation is open every day, all year round. Parc de Bagatelle: daily, opening hours vary according to season. Boats for hire are open from mid-February to the end of October: from 12pm to 5pm, Monday to Friday, and from 10am to 6pm at weekends."]

label: Le Petit Bain
comment: Le Petit Bain, near the Joséphine Baker swimming pool, is a 45m floating cultural facility. With a 250-seat auditorium, a 60-seat restaurant, a creative space and a resource center, it offers a magnificent view over the Seine. An atypical venue showcasing contemporary music and new artistic forms through workshops and open-air concerts, it's a must for culture-lovers in Paris.

additional_information: ['The restaurant and terrace are open Tuesday and Wednesday from 6pm to midnight; Thursday to Saturday from 6pm to 2am; Sunday from 4pm to midnight. The concert hall: depending on the program.']

label: Musée - Maison Poincaré
comment: The Institut Henri Poincaré opens the Maison Poincaré, a 900m² museum in the heart of the Latin Quarter in Paris. This space dedicated to mathematics features a permanent exhibition organized around seven themes: Modeling, Becoming, Sharing, Inventing, Connecting, Visualizing and Breathing. Visitors can manipulate, interact and view immersive videos. Temporary exhibitions, special events and workshops enrich the cultural program. A fascinating immersion in the world of mathematics and its concrete impact on everyday life.

comment: Alain Mikli designs eyewear frames that dress the eyes with as much care as they would dress a person. Combining style and comfort, Mikli's creations are veritable must-haves on the optical market. A perfect combination of design, quality and elegance to enhance the eyes.

label: Ice Kube Bar
comment: Discover the Ice Kube Bar in Paris: an authentic ice bar for an icy experience lasting up to 25 minutes in the heart of the Kube Hôtel, in the La Chapelle district. -18 degrees, 20 tons of ice, new decor every year. Featured vodka, served in a variety of ways. Down jackets and gloves provided on arrival. A unique adventure for the most daring! Book now.

A great opportunity to let yourself be carried away by the music in a convivial atmosphere.

comment: Ideally located in the heart of the Marais, close to Saint-Merri church, Le Chant des Voyelles is a must on rue des Lombards, renowned for its friendly atmosphere. The chef offers traditional French cuisine, featuring fresh, high-quality produce. Its terrace on the pedestrian street, open all year round, is perfect for enjoying the lively neighborhood. An ideal place to discover the oyster bar as soon as you enter and whet your appetite!

label: Le Train Bleu
comment: The luxury Brasserie de la Gare de Lyon, inaugurated in 1900 by Emile Loubet, is a historic gem. Its 2 rooms are listed historic monuments, and its 41 paintings illustrate the landscapes of the trains on the Paris-Lyon-Mediterranean network. Le Train Bleu, frequented by Coco Chanel, Brigitte Bardot and Dali, is famous for its high-profile clientele. With almost 500 covers served daily, its success is undeniable. A partner of Michel Rostang, the Brasserie offers generous, traditional cuisine, making it a must at Gare de Lyon.

Pose with your idols and leave with a memorable photo album! A visit full of surprises for you, your family and your friends!

comment: This trendy New York loft, located in a lively neighborhood, charms with its large windows letting in soft light. Its sophisticated cocktail bar and elegant pizzeria promise a relaxed yet chic atmosphere, perfect for evenings out with friends or romantic rendezvous. Discover this unique place where flavors and atmospheres mingle for an unforgettable experience, whether you love cocktails or pizzas.

It's a convivial place where you can eat, drink, relax, listen to music and even dance. A space open to all, conducive to relaxation and encounters.

comment: The designer is acclaimed for her sequined tote bag, combining delicate lace and sheer fabrics. Her unique creations conquered fashionistas the world over, propelling her to the top of the fashionable designer league. Her innovative style seduces with originality and elegance for every occasion. Her passion for fashion and her talent fascinate and inspire lovers of refined, original style.

comment: Decorated in the characteristic style of the Southwest, this restaurant invites you to discover the delights of Basque cuisine. Prepared with care and passion, the specialties on offer feature quality products for an authentic culinary experience. A gourmet getaway guaranteed in a warm and friendly setting.

label: Dilettantes
comment: Located near rue Gît le c?ur, the Maison du Champagne offers over 130 rare champagnes from grand cru terroirs, all crafted by artisan winemakers. In its 17th-century cellar, enjoy a duo tasting from an exceptional selection. Discover confidential cuvées to savor the subtleties of terroir, grape variety, year and blend. Learn how to pair this wine with a meal, not just as an aperitif, and leave with your favorite cuvées to prolong this unique taste experience. A charming and refined setting for an unforgettable experience.

label: Institut culturel italien
comment: The Institut Culturel Italien de Paris, nestled in the "Quartier des Ministres", is fully committed to promoting the Italian language and culture. At the heart of its missions are courses dedicated to the Italian language and culture, as well as cultural events highlighting Italy and its artistic, scientific and cultural wealth. A true bridge between France and Italy, where strong and lasting cultural links are forged.

label: Maison Gainsbourg
comment: The Maison Gainsbourg on rue de Verneuil in Paris has two sites. At 5 bis, Serge Gainsbourg's historic home has remained unchanged since his death in 1991, offering an intimate insight into his life. At number 14, a museum retraces his life and career. The bookshop-boutique and café Gainsbarre complete the experience. The Maison Gainsbourg is aiming for 100,000 visitors a year, with a varied program designed to share the artist's collection and unveil every facet of his work.

Designed by experts, these tours offer a unique approach to the City of Light. Whether you're a professional or just curious, let us guide you on a variety of tours, small-group outings or tailor-made premium tours. Immerse yourself in the architectural soul of Paris!

The Menu Régional offers a variety of French and international dishes, including Croquemonsieur, Onion Soup Gratinée, Club Sandwich and Caesar Salad. On weekdays, the Carte Blanche offers an exceptional gastronomic experience, supervised by Chef Sébastien Giroud.

Explore unusual neighborhoods and little-known places, and sample Parisian gastronomy. An unforgettable experience combining history and modernity.

label: Jardin21
comment: Located on the banks of the Canal de l'Ourcq in the 19th arrondissement of Paris, Jardin21 is a 1,850 m² oasis of greenery. Featuring an urban vegetable garden, terrace and covered areas, this atypical venue offers a variety of activities: sports, gardening, artisan markets, concerts and DJ sets. Open from Wednesday to Sunday from June to September, Jardin21 is the perfect place to spend convivial moments with friends and family. Discover the program on jardin21.fr.

label: Paul Beuscher
comment: Since 1850, Paul Beuscher, the iconic music store, has been at the heart of Paris. Passionate about the transmission of music, we welcome you to our modern, spacious premises. Guitars, pianos, drums, strings, wind instruments, home studios, sheet music... an incomparable choice. With personalized advice and try-out areas, take the time to find the instrument that's right for you. At Paul Beuscher, satisfaction is guaranteed, and music is just waiting for you.

comment: The food market on boulevard Magenta, between the Gare du Nord and Gare de l'Est stations, is a veritable gourmet paradise. Italian, African, Portuguese, Asian, Moroccan, Lebanese specialties... Two florists, a cafeteria, alteration and shoe repair services complete the offer. A lively place offering visitors a unique experience.

label: Cité des Fleurs
comment: In the past, residents of this housing estate were required to plant three trees in their garden to preserve nature in the city. Today, this charming flower-filled paved driveway in Paris offers calm and charm. The trees provide shade, and the flowers attract butterflies and birds, creating an oasis of tranquillity. Residents are delighted with this initiative, which has transformed their neighborhood into a friendly place to relax.

comment: After Dior and Hermès, Pierre Hardy created his own brand of shoes and bags, blending design and architecture. His brand combines tradition and modernity, seducing with its audacity and savoir-faire.

label: Turtle

Choose "Gustave Eiffel" or "Napoleon" for immersion in the heart of Paris, or "Henry IV" for a dive into the city's history. Includes: bike privatization, photo breaks, capacity for one or two passengers. Discover Paris in a unique way!

comment: The Hammam Medina Center, between La Villette and Belleville, offers an authentic wellness getaway. An oriental ambience conducive to absolute relaxation, with sauna, hot marble stone, relaxation room and swimming pool. Treatments provided by professionals. Afterwards, enjoy a gourmet break in the hammam restaurant, where you can sample exquisite pastries and dishes.

label: Hôtel de Polignac
comment: Built in 1901 by architect Henri Grandpierre for Winaretta Singer, the Hôtel de Polignac is an 18th-century architectural gem. Since 1945, it has been home to the Fondation Singer-Polignac, founded in 1928 by the princess. The Foundation supports the arts, letters and sciences through conferences, symposia and musical residencies. A magnificent residence dedicated to culture and learning.

label: Église réformée d'Auteuil
comment: Founded in 1895, the Église Réformée d'Auteuil is housed in a neo-Gothic building. Every Sunday, many faithful gather here for worship. The parish organizes activities for all, prayer times and cultural events. Involved in local life, the parish takes part in solidarity initiatives. Come and join this warm and welcoming community, where everyone can grow in their faith.

label: Casa Luca
comment: La Casa Luca, a designer trattoria near the Champs-Élysées, was designed by architect Pierre-Yves Rochon. Combining warmth and modernity, this restaurant blends designer furniture and warm tones to create a cosy atmosphere. Perfect for enjoying Italian gastronomy in a trendy and pleasant setting. An ideal place to relax and enjoy a convivial moment.

label: Crypte archéologique de l'Ile de la Cité
comment: The archaeological crypt on the Ile de la Cité, beneath Notre-Dame Cathedral in Paris, is the largest of its kind in Europe. It reveals the urban and architectural evolution of the island. Foundations and remains of buildings from Gallo-Roman times to the 18th century fascinate visitors. Slide shows, models and guided tours for all enrich this captivating exploration.

label: Église Saint-Germain-des-Prés
comment: The church of Saint-Germain-des-Prés, one of the oldest religious buildings in Paris, features a Romanesque nave, imposing columns and richly decorated capitals. Its Gothic choir, illuminated by colorful stained glass windows, exudes a serene atmosphere. The gothic capitals in the ambulatory are an invitation to reflect. A stroll through this edifice offers a unique experience.

label: Théâtre des Bouffes Parisiens
comment: Founded in 1827, the Théâtre des Bouffes Parisiens, the jewel in the crown of the Palais Royal, is a landmark on the Parisian cultural scene. Renowned for its rich program of comedies, it was directed for over 20 years by the talented actor Jean-Claude Brialy, from 1986 to 2007. A must-see address for theater lovers in search of quality entertainment.

comment: Pink Mamma is an Italian trattoria renowned for its Tuscan-style grilled meat. Set over 4 floors in a handsome SoPi building, it offers fresh, homemade products. You can also discover a fine selection of Italian wines. As a bonus, affordable prices for an authentic taste journey.

comment: Alain Ducasse's factory, near the Bastille, offers a unique coffee experience. The Michelin-starred chef offers eight "haute cuisine" coffees, to enjoy on the premises or to take away. Each bean is carefully selected for exceptional flavours. The industrial-design space, with its 1930s pewter counter and top-of-the-range equipment, is a must for coffee enthusiasts in search of authenticity and quality.

label: Baby Dior
comment: In 2007, to mark the fortieth anniversary of "Baby", Christian Dior opened two new areas dedicated to children's ready-to-wear. The address at 26, avenue Montaigne houses the baby collection, while the one at 28 offers clothes for 2-12 year-olds. An initiative that illustrates the luxury brand's commitment to the world of children's fashion.

label: Église Sainte-Anne de la Butte-aux-Cailles
comment: Sainte-Anne de la Butte-aux-Cailles church, built in Paris in 1912, is an architectural gem in a unique Romanesque-Byzantine style. The Mauméjean brothers created breathtaking stained glass windows and mosaics inside, carefully chosen to create an enchanting atmosphere. The light penetrating through the stained glass illuminates the interior in a magical way, offering visitors a moment of meditation in the history and beauty of sacred art.

With 9,000 m² of space, it offers a wide variety of shops, from ready-to-wear to delicatessens. A must for shoppers in the heart of the City of Light.

On the first floor, two rooms decorated with operetta and film posters plunge you into a Parisian ambience to enjoy the great classics of French cuisine. Upstairs, three private lounges can accommodate from 20 to 100 guests. An authentic culinary experience in the heart of the capital.

Let yourself be immersed in the inspiring atmosphere of their boutique, where every purchase of a diary, notebook or photo album becomes an exceptional emotional experience. Unleash your creativity and discover a refined universe where every item is precisely designed to enhance your ideas and projects.

Made from beef, lamb or chicken, they are the perfect accompaniment to lentils, mashed potatoes or risotto, all with delicious sauces. The trendy atmosphere of this chic cantine adds a friendly touch to the culinary experience. And what's more, the prices are affordable. An address not to be missed!

label: Le Béguin
comment: Immerse yourself in the 50s at Le Béguin, between Place de Clichy and Trinité! This retro bistro, tucked away in a cul-de-sac, seduces with its vintage decor: zinc, charcoal stove, retro posters, neon lights, Formica furniture... Enjoy simple, tasty cuisine, with farm-fresh, artisanal and organic produce. Rock'n'roll atmosphere, swing and entertainment guaranteed! A warm welcome and impeccable service complete the experience. Perhaps you'll bump into lively performers after their shows in one of the many nearby theaters.
description: Immerse yourself in the 50s at Le Béguin, between Place de Clichy and Trinité! This retro bistro, tucked away in a cul-de-sac, seduces with its vintage decor: zinc, charcoal stove, retro posters, neon lights, Formica furniture... Enjoy simple, tasty cuisine, with farm-fresh, artisanal and organic produce. Rock'n'roll atmosphere, swing and entertainment guaranteed! A warm welcome and impeccable service complete the experience. Perhaps you'll bump into lively performers after their shows in one of the many nearby theaters.

label: Promotrain - Le Petit Train de Montmartre
comment: Discover Montmartre on a 40-minute guided tour, ideal for exploring the picturesque village that inspired Picasso and Van Gogh. From the Moulin Rouge to the Sacré-C?ur with a view over Paris, via the Amphitheatre, the Arena, Saint-Pierre Church and Place du Tertre, immerse yourself in the unique atmosphere of this emblematic district. Don't miss the Espace Dalí and end your tour at Place Blanche for a truly enriching Montmartre experience!

label: Musée de Minéralogie
comment: The Museum of Mineralogy, a 19th-century building, exhibits over 4,000 samples of minerals, rocks, meteorites and precious stones. The fruit of a long tradition of collecting and constant enrichment, it reveals the beauty and diversity of the mineral world. This legacy of the cabinets of curiosities bears witness to the evolution of knowledge in mineralogy. A French scientific heritage that raises awareness of the challenges of mineral exploitation.

comment: The Mouton-Duvernet food market, ideally located between Alésia and Denfert-Rochereau, just a stone's throw from the famous rue Daguerre, will delight lovers of fresh, organic produce. This must-visit store offers a wide range of fruit and vegetables grown in an environmentally-friendly way. An invitation to discovery and tasting for all lovers of good food and well-being.

label: Breguet
comment: Since 1775, Breguet has been an essential name in luxury watchmaking, attracting an illustrious clientele including Marie Antoinette and Napoleon. Each timepiece embodies exceptional craftsmanship with noble materials for elegant style. In addition to watches, Breguet offers collections of fine jewelry, sophisticated cufflinks and fine writing instruments. A brand of excellence and timeless elegance.

comment: Located near the Saint-Lazare train station, this cinema complex has five screening rooms. Ideally placed for travelers in transit or local cinephiles, this establishment offers a diversified program to satisfy all audiences. Enjoy a unique cinematic experience in a modern, comfortable setting, just a stone's throw from the hustle and bustle of the capital.

label: Église Saint-Joseph des Épinettes
comment: Built between 1909 and 1910, the Épinettes church houses the bloodied shirt of Hippolyte Debroise, murdered by anarchists in 1907 during the Corpus Christi procession in Dugny. This moving fact is part of its history. The church was consecrated by Monseigneur Amette, Archbishop of Paris. An 1898 Cavaillé-Coll organ adds a musical and historical touch to this place of mystery and emotion.

label: Cinq Mondes - Spa Paris
comment: Located in the heart of Paris, in a pedestrian square, the Cinq Mondes spa invites you on a sensory voyage. With a surface area of 500 m², this haven of peace offers a unique experience by renewing rituals carefully selected from the four corners of the globe. A true urban escape where tradition blends with innovation to offer unforgettable moments of relaxation and well-being.

label: Cinéma Luminor - Hôtel de ville
comment: Inaugurated in 1914, the Luminor - Hôtel de ville cinema is a landmark in the Marais district. Specializing in auteur films, it is the venue for previews, press screenings and prestigious festivals such as Arte, and is involved in the "Enfances au cinéma" program, committed to introducing young audiences to the richness of the 7th art. Upstairs, a superb function room can accommodate up to a hundred people for private events.

comment: Since 1854, the renowned leather goods house has been a benchmark in luxury. In 2005, it opened a flagship store in Paris, bringing together emblematic collections for a unique shopping experience. Each piece reflects the expertise and excellence of our craftsmen, perpetuating the tradition of elegance and quality. Flagship embodies heritage and innovation, attracting discerning customers in search of refinement. A must for lovers of French elegance.

label: Forum des images
comment: Founded in 1988, the Forum des images is a cultural venue renowned for its film screenings and exhibitions. Located in the 1st arrondissement, it offers themed cycles, festivals and debates. Under the direction of Claude Farge, the Forum des images attracts cinephiles with over 7,700 films in Paris. In September 2018, it opened TUMO Paris, a free digital creation school for teenagers aged 12 and over.

label: Conservatoire national supérieur de musique et de danse de Paris
comment: The Conservatoire de Paris trains 1,300 students with a passion for music, dance and new sound technologies. Every year, these talented students perform in shows combining music and choreography, providing a springboard for up-and-coming artists. A place of culture and artistic creation, it contributes to the dissemination of art, combining tradition and modernity. A veritable hotbed of talent for lovers of the performing arts.

label: Marché Daumesnil
comment: The Daumesnil market, in the heart of the 12th arrondissement, is the longest market in Paris, with almost 1,500 linear meters. Here you'll find a wide variety of organic produce, as well as some thirty stalls filled with fresh fruit, vegetables and fish. In addition to food, there are non-food stalls to suit all customer needs. A must-see for food and local produce enthusiasts.

comment: Founded in 1966, the "Compagnie Française de l?Orient et de la Chine" (CFOC) is a benchmark for Chinese crafts enthusiasts. Specializing in pottery, terracotta tableware and lanterns, CFOC also offers elegant yak and shantung garments. Immerse yourself in a world rich in Chinese finesse and tradition, with unique and authentic pieces. Discover ancestral Chinese art through CFOC's original creations.

comment: Discover Madame Brasserie, a friendly address in the heart of the Eiffel Tower. Enjoy a panoramic view of Paris with family and friends. On the first floor, relax in the lounge bar. Upstairs, enjoy family-style cuisine at lunchtime and refined dishes in the evening by chef Thierry Marx. Contemporary brasserie cuisine, using local, seasonal produce. Succumb to simple, generous dishes for an exceptional culinary experience.

label: Berko
comment: Located in the heart of the historic Marais district, Berko is the temple of cupcakes in Paris. This mini-restaurant on rue Rambuteau offers a warm, colorful setting, typical of cupcakes. With a wide range of flavors, the cupcakes are irresistible. In addition to cheesecakes and reductions, Berko offers lunch menus with tarts, bagels, salads and soups to satisfy every craving. A must for lovers of sweet and savory treats.

label: Château de Bagatelle
comment: In 1775, the Comte d'Artois, brother of Louis XVI, bought a small château dating from 1720 in the Bois de Boulogne, nicknamed the "place of libertinage". Marie-Antoinette and he set out to rebuild the château in two months. Work began on September 21, 1777, and the challenge was successfully met, with the inauguration taking place on November 26 of the same year. An architectural feat that testifies to the speed and expertise of the time.

Both practical and entertaining, the Armand Massard pool will satisfy swimmers in search of relaxation or sporting challenges.

comment: The Musée du quai Branly - Jacques Chirac, near the Eiffel Tower, exhibits 3,500 works of art from different continents. Designed by Jean Nouvel, the museum's original architecture blends with its wild garden. After your visit, take advantage of the restaurant Les Ombres or Café Jacques. It's a place where art and culture meet, offering an enriching experience among the great museums of Paris.

label: Fondation Dubuffet - Paris
comment: When the Fondation Dubuffet was created in 1973 - by Jean Dubuffet himself - its aim was twofold: to preserve the works of the painter and precursor of Art Brut, and to guarantee public access to them. Today, the Fondation Dubuffet's mission is to acquire and preserve any object or production likely to be of interest in understanding the artist's life and work. The Fondation Dubuffet is headquartered in a private mansion in the 6th arrondissement of Paris, and also has an annex in Périgny-sur-Yerres, in the Val-de-Marne.

label: Shin Jung
comment: Nestled in the 8th arrondissement of Paris, away from the hustle and bustle of Saint-Lazare station, the Shin Jung restaurant opens its doors to you. Immerse yourself in a peaceful, elegant atmosphere and savor authentic Korean cuisine combining simplicity and generosity. A warm address where exotic flavors mingle with refinement. A gourmet interlude not to be missed. For food lovers, a second address awaits you at 54-58 rue Mademoiselle, 75015, also in Paris.

label: Musée de la Légion d’honneur et des ordres de Chevalerie
comment: Opposite the Musée d'Orsay is the Musée de la Légion d?honneur et des ordres de Chevalerie, retracing the history of French and foreign decorations from the Middle Ages to the present day. Housed in the Hôtel de Salm, built in 1782, this emblematic building is brimming with Napoleonic memorabilia and houses the Grand Chancellery of the Legion of Honor. A captivating immersion in the world of honors and distinctions, highlighting the history of awards.

These shoes are not just accessories, but a true style icon for French fashionistas.

It is distinguished by its state-of-the-art "Poséidon" safety system, which prevents any risk of drowning. Nestled in the Auteuil racecourse, this facility combines elegance and technology to delight swimmers.

label: Musée du Barreau de Paris
comment: Immerse yourself in the history of France through the museum, with centuries of events told through works of art and original documents. Discover the lives of emblematic figures such as Louis XVI, Marie-Antoinette, Léon Gambetta and Raymond Poincaré. From the Dreyfus affair to the Zola trial, explore the underbelly of justice and politics. The collection of pleadings offers a unique insight into the world of lawyers, from the defense strategies of Chauveau-Lagarde to Jacques Isorni. A fascinating plunge into judicial history, for a better understanding of the past and current issues.

An unforgettable culinary experience in the heart of Paris.

label: Monument aux morts pour la France en opérations extérieures
comment: Located in Paris's Parc André-Citroën, the Monument aux Morts pour la France en opérations extérieures (Monument to those who died in France's overseas operations) pays tribute to the soldiers who have fallen since 1963. Inaugurated in 2019, it comprises a monumental sculpture and a wall bearing the names of over 600 soldiers. Free access all year round.

label: Karl Lagerfeld
comment: In June 2013, Karl Lagerfeld, the emblematic designer of the House of Chanel, inaugurated his boutique in the trendy Marais district of Paris. In an elegant black-and-white setting, you'll find women's and men's ready-to-wear collections, as well as a cutting-edge selection of accessories, books and objects chosen by the designer. A shopping experience not to be missed, with the added bonus of fitting rooms worthy of the name!

label: Temple de l'église protestante unie de Montparnasse-Plaisance
comment: In the heart of Montparnasse is the United Protestant Church of Montparnasse-Plaisance, founded in 1855. This historic parish of the Église Protestante Unie de France is home to an open community. A historic and contemporary place of worship, it gathers a large number of faithful every week. A spiritual and social pillar of the neighborhood, it offers a wide range of activities. Come and discover this jewel of Parisian religious heritage on your next visit.

This historic parish of the Église Protestante Unie de France is home to an open community. A historic and contemporary place of worship, it gathers a large number of faithful every week. A spiritual and social pillar of the neighborhood, it offers a wide range of activities. Come and discover this jewel of Parisian religious heritage on your next visit.

label: Musée de la Vie romantique
comment: Nestled in Pigalle's La Nouvelle Athènes district, the Musée de la Vie Romantique, former home of Ary Scheffer, plunges you into the artistic world of Romanticism. Discover portraits, antique furniture and paintings by George Sand and her contemporaries. Exhibitions, concerts and events enhance the experience. The garden is also home to the Rose Bakery tea room for a gourmet break. A historic and soothing place to discover.

label: Boutique Talents
comment: Located between the Étoile and Ternes districts of Paris, the Talents boutique, created by Ateliers d?Art de France in 2001, sells one-off pieces and small series, each crafted by a designer in his or her own art studio in France. The Suki Paris leather goods brand was born in 2015 from the meeting of Amandine Petit and Bruno Simon. In the 17th arrondissement of Paris, they create their collections, which they aim to be timeless, ethical and sustainable.

comment: The Musée de la Chasse et de la Nature store offers a selection of books and exhibition catalogs published by the museum since 1999. Take this opportunity to purchase limited editions, also available by mail order. Immerse yourself in the fascinating world of hunting and nature through these precious publications.

label: Crazy Horse Paris
comment: Immerse yourself in a world of beauty and sensuality at the heart of Parisian nightlife. On Avenue George V, close to the Champs-Élysées, discover the most avant-garde Cabaret in Paris. Its brand-new show, "Totally Crazy", promises a unique and spellbinding experience. Don't miss this exceptional experience!

label: Phono Museum Paris
comment: The Phono Museum Paris, temple of sound, traces the 140-year history of sound recording. From the first phonographs to MP3 files, nearly 300 functional machines illustrate the evolution of technology. Posters and photos of artists complete the visit. Located at the foot of Montmartre, the museum reflects the artistic soul of the neighborhood, from the Belle Époque to the Moulin Rouge, from Mistinguett to Josephine Baker. Immerse yourself in the captivating world of recorded sound!

label: Bateau-Lavoir - Cité d'artistes
comment: Located in the Montmartre district, the Bateau-Lavoir is an emblematic site where some twenty artists have made their studios their home. Pablo Picasso, Henri Matisse and Georges Braque all frequented this place steeped in history and conducive to creativity. To visit this mythical place, it's imperative to make an appointment, and discover the unique atmosphere that has inspired so many renowned artists.

label: Collection de Minéraux - Sorbonne Université
comment: Sorbonne Université's Mineral Collection boasts 2,000 samples from all over the world. These minerals, selected from the most remarkable species, are essential to geology, industry and art. Presented in 24 panoramic showcases, these treasures are inspired by the Museum of the Crown Jewels of Iran. Ranked among the most prestigious in the world, this is an exceptional collection in France.

comment: The Galerie d?Architecture, located in the heart of the Marais district, is a space dedicated to international contemporary architecture. Since 1999, it has been showcasing current architectural creation, offering visitors a lively and inspiring venue. The gallery supports young talent while exhibiting renowned architects, landscape architects and designers from all over the world. A must for architecture enthusiasts in search of inspiration.

label: Église Saint-Louis-en-l'Île
comment: Built between 1664 and 1726 by the architect Le Vau, the church features an original bell tower with a clock dating from 1741. Inside, works of art such as Coypel's "Les Pèlerins d'Emmaüs" (1746) and Fra Angelico's "Annunciation" can be admired. There's also a "Saint-François de Salle" by Noël Hallé and a painting by Carle Van Loo (1742) depicting Saint John and Saint Peter healing a lame man. A must-see visit to discover this exceptional artistic heritage.

label: The American Church in Paris
comment: Founded in 1814, the American Protestant Church of Paris is a historic institution for the Protestant community in France. Established in its current building since 1931, it offers a spiritual and cultural setting in the heart of the capital, with religious services, English classes, concerts and wedding celebrations. Open and diversified, it is a must for American Protestants visiting Paris and for those in search of spirituality.

And why not take advantage of the terrace for an alfresco break. A must for lovers of good food.

An unmissable gastronomic getaway for Mediterranean cuisine lovers.

Don't miss your chance to feast on the exquisite dishes of this atypical cantine. You're sure to find something to your liking among the options on offer.

label: Jardin sauvage Saint-Vincent
comment: Once neglected, this sloping garden has been transformed into a wild eden where elderberries, foxgloves, brambles, ivy and small country creatures have taken up residence. The town?s landscape gardeners brought this sleepy haven of greenery back to life, but soon abandoned their gardening tools. This fragile and poetic place is now preserved to study its ecosystem, observe its biodiversity, contemplate the pond's inhabitants, and appreciate the charm of the wild grasses.

label: Musée de l'Armée - Invalides
comment: Since 1861, the tomb of Napoleon I has been housed at the Hôtel national des Invalides in Paris. Once a hospital for wounded soldiers, it is now an Army museum with a rich collection of military art and history. Armor, weapons, uniforms, paintings and photos from different eras are on display. Interactive activities allow visitors to relive great historic battles. A must-see for history and military art enthusiasts.

label: Porte de Saint-Denis
comment: The majestic Porte Saint-Denis, designed by François Blondel and Michel Anguier in 1672 to celebrate Louis XIV, sits gracefully on the boulevard of the same name. Inspired by Rome's Arch of Titus, the 25-meter-high Porte Saint-Denis replaces an earlier medieval gate built by Charles V, and is a testament to its classical elegance. Opening onto the dynamic Faubourg Saint-Denis, this monument steeped in history blends glorious past with vibrant modernity.

comment: Founded in La Baule, the generous-hearted chocolatier opened its first store in France in 2004. Since then, a number of outlets have sprung up, including the Parisian boutique, nestled on the outskirts of the famous Butte Montmartre. Here, the great classics of patisserie and other sweet delights (chocolates, macaroons...) are reinvented by the talented master patissier-chocolatier. An address where flavors and creativity meet to the delight of gourmets.

Immerse yourself in a unique experience where waiter-magicians enliven your meal with magic tricks. Then head downstairs for interactive and funny shows in an intimate atmosphere with only 50 seats. Don't miss this magical, convivial evening!

comment: Located between the Gare de l'Est and the Canal Saint-Martin, the Maison de l'architecture en Île-de-France is nestled in the former Couvent des Récollets. Transformed into a multi-purpose venue, the former chapel now hosts meetings and shows. Conceived as a space for sharing and dialogue, this unique venue is open to both professionals and city dwellers in search of architectural discoveries.

label: Église réformée de la Bastille, Temple protestant du Foyer de l'Âme
comment: Le Foyer de l'Âme, affiliated to the Protestant Church of France, near Bastille, was founded in 1907 by Pastor Charles Wagner. With a rich history, the parish brings together a community committed to solidarity actions. With its imposing architecture and open spirituality, it embodies Pastor Wagner's values of sharing, tolerance and love of neighbor. The parish responds to needs for a better world.

label: Théâtre national de l’Opéra Comique
comment: The Opéra Comique, with its 300-year history, is a hidden treasure far from the Boulevard des Italiens. Despite closures and fires, this theater has reinvented itself and been reborn. Europe's first electrically powered theater, it was the inspiration for the Eiffel Tower. La Damnation de Faust and Carmen were created here. Today, the Opéra Comique remains a creative hotbed for contemporary shows. An eventful institution that fascinates opera lovers.

comment: In the Bois de Vincennes reserve, birds are protected while visitors can observe them. Shelters strategically placed along the streams offer birdwatchers the opportunity to admire both local species and passing migrants. A harmonious blend of conservation and birdwatching.

Considered the biggest in Paris, it awaits you to take part in exciting tournaments with great rewards in store. With 160 PCs, get ready for hours of intense gaming in a friendly, competitive atmosphere.

comment: Immerse yourself in subtle, delicate Korean cuisine, from seafood to meats to galettes. The hushed ambience and warm welcome complete this refined culinary experience. An address where you can savor exquisite dishes and experience a true moment of delight and conviviality.

label: Théâtre Fontaine
comment: The Théâtre Fontaine, at 10 rue Pierre Fontaine between Place Blanche and Place de Clichy, is steeped in history. Prior to its opening in 1951, the site had a number of different lives: cemetery, plumbing factory, German cabaret during the Second World War. Today, this emblematic Parisian theater presents successful contemporary plays, establishing itself as one of the capital's key cultural venues.

Renowned artists, attractive prices and a wide selection of wines make Le Truskel a popular address on the Parisian nightlife scene. Ideal for prolonging the evening in a vibrant, festive atmosphere. A must for night owls in search of live music and lively encounters!

label: Glazed
comment: In the heart of SoPi (South Pigalle) on the gourmet Rue des Martyrs, Glazed is a must for ice-cream lovers in Paris. Original creations such as "Shake my nuts" (praline and hazelnuts), "Pussy griotte" (morello cherries and blackcurrant pepper) or "Black sugar sex magic" (dark chocolate, wasabi, ginger) offer surprising flavors. Glazed favors a locavore approach with locally sourced products. Ideal for a responsible gourmet break in Paris.

Not to be missed!

label: Folies Bergère
comment: Immerse yourself in the mythical world of the Folies Bergère, a legendary 19th-century theater that seduced large audiences with its Music-Hall revues. Discover its mysteries on a private one-hour guided tour, where legends such as Josephine Baker, Dalida and Jean-Paul Gaultier shone. For over two hundred years, this theater has made its mark on the international art scene with sensational events. Let yourself be carried away by its incredible history.

label: Le Mélo d'Amélie
comment: Le Mélo d'Amélie, in the heart of Paris near rue Étienne Marcel, is renowned for its warm atmosphere and quality shows. Original and inventive comedies attract large audiences, highlighting the Parisian scene. A meeting place for theater lovers, this theater is a breeding ground for talent, mixing established artists with promising young talents. Come and experience unique moments in the heart of the capital!

label: Pavillon de l'Ermitage
comment: Built between 1723 and 1727, this pavilion is the last vestige of the Bagnolet estate belonging to the Duchess of Orléans, daughter of Louis XIV. This Regency-style folie is a unique jewel. The three salons open to the public feature "grisaille" paintings and Greek-style decoration. Today, this pavilion is on display in the Square Debrousse, between the Père Lachaise cemetery and the Porte de Bagnolet, a precious testimony to a prestigious past.

label: La librairie portugaise et brésilienne
comment: Since its creation in 1986 by Michel Chandeigne, the Portuguese and Brazilian bookshop has been a reference in France. Specializing in Lusophone literature, it offers a wide selection of books on these fascinating cultures. A true haven for lovers of literature from elsewhere. An invaluable address for exploring these rich and varied worlds.

label: Ferme de Paris
comment: Since 1989, Ferme de Paris has been promoting sustainable food, urban agriculture and animal welfare, while respecting the environment. Orchards, vegetable gardens, green barnyards, permaculture, pastures and animal shelters offer total immersion. Workshops, training courses and tours are available weekdays by appointment, as well as on weekends for educational activities. Formerly the Georges Ville Farm (1824-1897), this historic site with Second Empire buildings attracts many curious visitors.

label: The Kooples
comment: The Kooples, created in 2008 by the creators of Comptoir des Cotonniers, offers a unique concept: a boutique with a pure black-and-white style, clothes with a quasi-unisex design, a British rock look and glamorous couples as ambassadors. A brand that combines sobriety and elegance, for a resolutely modern and daring style.

label: Marks & Spencer Food Châtelet-les-Halles
comment: No need to take the Channel Tunnel for fans of Marks & Spencer Food, the famous English brand born in 1884! Now, aficionados can treat themselves in the heart of Paris to the legendary crumpets, muffins, mince pies and shortbreads. With 8 boutiques dedicated exclusively to English gastronomy in the Paris region, it's now easier than ever to find these delights across the Channel. Long live culinary diversity!

label: Square Jehan Rictus
comment: Located on the Place des Abbesses in Montmartre, the Square Jehan Rictus is famous for its "je t'aime" wall. This wall, made up of 612 glazed lava tiles, is inscribed with these sweet words in over 250 different languages, symbolizing universal love. A poetic landmark where lovers from all over the world come to contemplate this unique work of art.

label: Halle Secrétan
comment: In 1868, Victor Baltard erected this magnificent metal structure in the 19th arrondissement, between the Bassin de la Villette and the Parc des Buttes-Chaumont. Transformed into a covered market, it houses food stalls, a Greek restaurant called Yaya open daily, a fitness room, a toy library and various shops. A lively, diverse place that delights visitors with its richness and conviviality.

label: Nocturne Rive Droite
comment: For over 15 years, Nocturne Rive Droite has been bringing together art professionals in the 8th arrondissement of Paris. Every year, this not-to-be-missed event features vernissages and exhibitions showcasing the work of carefully selected artists. Over 70 establishments open their doors, offering visitors an immersive immersion in contemporary art. A not-to-be-missed annual event for culture and aesthetics enthusiasts.

label: Saint Laurent Paris (38 Faubourg)
comment: The famous couturier, who died in 2008, had a profound impact on the history of women's ready-to-wear. Today, his iconic brand continues to shine thanks to the talented Anthony Vaccarello. In a bid to perpetuate the excellence and refinement that characterize this renowned house, the designer infuses his creativity while respecting the legacy left by the great couturier.

label: La Cachette
comment: Located in the 13th arrondissement of Paris, La Cachette is a theater dedicated to children. Founded by Jean-Pierre Idatte in 1973, Compagnie des 3 Chardons offers a varied repertoire of shows for 2-8 year-olds. With nineteen creations combining actors and puppets, the troupe invites young and old to share playful, poetic moments in the company of Eloi, Pitou, Mirabelle, Tchico, Leïla, Malo... An experience for the whole family!

label: Arènes de Lutèce et square Capitan
comment: The Arènes de Lutèce, historic monuments of ancient Lutetia (Paris), are listed. Open free of charge every day, these arenas dating from the 1st to 2nd centuries could accommodate 15,000 spectators. Visitors can see the actors' dressing rooms, the stage and lapidary elements. Along with the Thermes de Cluny, these are the only Gallo-Roman remains in Paris. A must-see visit to immerse yourself in the history of the French capital.

label: adidas arena
comment: The adidas arena, built for the Paris 2024 Olympics, is a major legacy. With its varied programming (sport, e-sport, concerts), it's a dynamic space. Its gymnasiums and warm-up area make it a must-see venue. Now home to Paris basketball, it reinforces its role in Parisian sport.

comment: Discover at René Derhy a selection of pieces from the previous year's collection at reduced prices. Take advantage of this opportunity to stand out from the crowd by adopting a trendy and daring style, without compromising your budget. Treat yourself to outfits that reflect your personality and originality, while staying at the cutting edge of fashion.

label: Paroisse Sainte-Clotilde
comment: The parish church of Sainte-Clotilde, the first neo-Gothic church built in Paris in the 19th century, stands out for its remarkable architecture, just a stone's throw from Les Invalides. Its majestic organ, attributed to Cavaillé-Coll, enchants music lovers. Also of note is the Chapelle de Jésus-Enfant, at number 29, a listed historic monument.

label: L'Antre Magique
comment: Located in the Saint-Georges district of Paris, L'Antre Magique is one of the city's leading magic venues. Founded in 1996 by renowned magician Christian Gambin, this emblematic venue has also been home to the Ecole de Magie de Paris since 2000. The program includes plays, musicals and magic shows, as well as conferences, private lessons, visual act creation and team building. An enchanting universe where magic works at every level!
